ValuesSurvey:
Avoid a black and white world view. Understand that life is shades of grey, and everyone has a reason for their actions. If someone or something tries to explain a person or event in completely black and white terms and tells you "That's the entire story!", be suspicious.

Strive for positivity. In today's world it's extremely easy to get mired in negativity and snark. It's not healthy; find the good in life and focus on that, bring up a smile, and try to spread that positivity around. Negativity has never helped anyone.

Honor your commitments, and be honest in all dealings. Pretty straightforward.

Stay curious. Don't simply accept things at face value; not sure what's going on with an event? Research it! See something interesting? Look into it! One of the great joys of living in this time period is access to information and knowledge.

Treat others as you'd like to be treated. This one is basically straight out of the Bible, and really doesn't need much explanation. Treat others with kindness whenever possible.

Realize that you don't have the answers, but strive for knowledge.

ValuesSurvey:
A value is what is considered important in life, what makes life worth living. A values is also something that help us decide what is right or wrong in moral term.

There are different kinds of values such as social, personal, universal, moral, spiritual, cultural etc.

Friendship, patience, tolerance and love can be consider as social values. Honesty, creativity, imagination and excellence can be consider as personal values. Peace, human dignity, equal human rights and freedom can be consider as universal values. Respect to others and ourselves, keep promises, show gratitude to others, encourage others are moral values. Purity, piety, meditation, self-discipline, self-control, devotion to god can be consider as spiritual values. Cultural values allows us to situate ourselves in relation to the society we live in.

All these values are important in life to achieve success and live healthy, happily, trusty.

Personally I practice four values in life.

Health is the greatest gift,
Contentment is the greatest wealth,
Trust is the best relative,
Liberated mind is the greatest bliss.

I gained health & happiness by following things in life.

Anybody can accept and practice three values Respect, Friendship and Excellence under any circumstance.

ValuesSurvey: The most important value that I have is autonomy. I want to be able to make my own choices. I want it to be my body and my choice. I want to decide for myself what is best. I want to live the lifestyle that I want because I want it and not have to answer to anyone. I want to read a book because I want to and not be shamed for it. I want to eat what I want to and not be judged. I want to believe what I want to believe and not be attacked for it. I want to be myself. I want to purchase the things I want to purchase and not have someone always looking over my shoulder or "being on their radar" and secretly making judgments about me that I am not adult enough or that I am to childish because I like to wear things with hearts or because I like to watch films on Disney Plus, or that I love to read books about fantasy worlds. The things that matters the most to me is that I can truly be myself in my relationships and not be shamed all the time because it doesn't look like what another person thinks is good for me. We are not all the same. We don't all want the same things. We should be free to love what we love and not have to defend it all the time. Who cares if it doesn't look like you? I am my own person. I have my own mind and my own beliefs. I don't have to be a cut out of another person. I don't care what another person believes is acceptable. I don't care what another person believes my faith should be. The most important thing to me is my autonomy. I am sick and tired of being treated like a child and watching the world treat grown adults like children who can not decide for themselves what they want to do with their own body. Our body is ours. It is not something that should ever be "owned" by someone else. No one should be able to tell me what I can and cannot do with my own body.

ValuesSurvey: My belief in family drives most of what I do each day.  I put myself before others and try to serve instead of take.  It is not always easy, but then that is where my Christian beliefs also guide and motivate.  I was taught those beliefs from my father and mother and extended family, so here we are back to family again.  I could name specific values, but really I am guided fundamentally by those family roots.  If something seems right or wrong, it is most likely a reflection or extension of that heritage.  And if I had to list a few of those guiding values, it would be the classic list we teach: love joy patience kindness goodness faithfulness gentleness and self-control.  If these are in my heart, it is going to be a good day.

ValuesSurvey: I try to live my life based on the principle of "live and let live". If someone is doing something that does not directly interfere with myself or others, I see no harm in it. This for me means that I do not put much worth in things like the "traditional family" or gender roles, and I believe that everyone should pursue their own happiness. I base a large amount of my beliefs on answering two questions: does this action harm the person doing it? Does this action harm others? As long as the answer to both of those questions is no, I see no issue with the activity, even if it is unusual or otherwise outside of the societal norm. When it comes to deciding between two choices, this also comes into play for me. I consider whether one of the choices would do harm to me or others, and if not, I choose the one that feels like it would do the most good for myself and others. This is a simple system, but I believe it has made me a happier person and has takes some stress out of my life.

Aside from that I woke up at around 7 each day, I made breakfast, and started on work. I ate lunch between 11:30 and 12:30, and then either continued work or continued on another project through the afternoon. Since it is close to Christmas, I took some time out of each evening to work on wrapping gifts and getting them ready for their recipients. I also have a cross stitch project that I finished Thursday, so I took some time out of my evening to get it washed and hung up to dry.

ValuesSurvey: Wow my values were instilled in me when I was a young girl. My parents taught me morals and values that have stayed with me my entire life. This topic brings tears to my eyes after what I just wrote because it is those, we love so much that are no longer here that we learned from and have instilled in us life lessons that will never leave us on this earth. I try to teach my son these same exact values and I am proud to see him become the man that I trained early on like my parents trained me. We are old fashioned, and I don't care those folks may call me that because I would take old fashioned any day then what I hear and see around me in today society. It is truly sad. I appreciate my upbringing even in the hardest of times because it taught me so many life values and principles. For sure.

I started my week off with a big grocery trip to buy stuff for baking Christmas cookies and cakes. There is only so many hours in a day and then have to play with the dog and take him out etc. Cook clean and always doing something around the house keeps me busy and some days I just want to lay down and watch tv all day but that is not an option in my life or so it seems. I do alot of praying each day and thinking this holiday is sad without my Mother who we lost this year. I lost my brother last year so holidays are very rough for me now. I try to be positive for my son though who also shares a Christmas Eve birthday. I think alot as I go about my daily chores and try to always remember and pray every day about all the beautiful memories my Mother and Brother and my Father who is no longer here as well gave to me. Life is not the same for sure and if I think too much on it it really makes me sad. They would not want me to be sad this I know. But it is hard not to be especially this time of year.

ValuesSurvey:
Above all else, I value loyalty. I strongly believe that you truly discover who your true friends are when you encounter a moment of need. If I am in a difficult situation, which rarely happens, I judge my family and friends on how they respond to my need(s) during this period. To be honest, I also judge myself the same way. When my family or friends are in need, I expect myself to assist them in any manner possible. If I don't, I don't consider myself worthy of their love and respect. 

Another important value that guides my life is honesty. If someone won't be honest with you, why in the world would you allow them to continue to be a part of your life? I understand that you can certainly encounter dishonest people that you have no control over, such as people at stores or businesses and work colleagues. Much like loyalty, however, I tend to judge people pretty quickly. If they show themselves to be dishonest in any way, I keep them at a distance or cut them out of my life entirely.
BehaviorsSurvey:
Much of the time I've spent during the past week is very mundane and redundant. I am a creature of habit and enjoy a predictable and well-structured life. 

Last weekend, I spent with my son, who I see every other weekend. We sat around and watched a lot of horror movies, as that's kind of our bonding activity now, since he is a teenager. We ate out a couple of times, fast food one day and pizza another. We also did some necessary chores around my apartment and played a couple of video games together. 

During the last 5 days of my work week, my days don't vary much. I get up, eat a keto-friendly breakfast. Work from home, in my den, until noon. I then go for a 3 mile run at lunch. After lunch, I drink a keto lunch-replacement shake and then work all afternoon. After work, I usually spend about 30 minutes doing resistance exercises. I then eat a healthy dinner. After dinner, I clean the dishes, play some piano, as I'm taking lessons, and then sit and watch TV until I go to bed. I'm usually texting with friends and playing on social media a bit in the evenings as well.

ValuesSurvey: Some of the most important values that guide my life have changed over time and some have been constant. I completely believe in the importance of honesty, in dealings with others and oneself. I believe that lies are unnecessary, and that the truth is neither good nor bad. I believe that it is important to always have an open mind. It is important to be curious about things and people and take all aspects of them into account. The funny thing is that you usually learn something about yourself in the process. I also believe that there is something good in everyone, so no one should be treated as a bad person. If you don't like someone, don't be around them. And lastly, my most odd belief and value is that God is my best friend. And I treat him as such. I say "hey how ya doin'?" and "whassup." I ask how his day went. I find that much nicer than constantly asking him for this and that without even so much as a how do you do.

ValuesSurvey: In general, I try to live my best life. I want to raise my daughters as good humans, so I'm strict but I also try to be fun. I discipline when they don't listen, or when they do something that I don't think is correct. I try to treat everyone in my life or that I even come across with respect, as I'd want them to treat me. I also have a rule where I don't put up with anything I shouldn't, as I've experienced a lot of negativity in my life and promised I would never put up with it again. I make mistakes, but I do try to learn from them as much as possible to avoid making them a second time. It's important for me to set a good example for all of my family, and help however I can. My partner is not good with any technology, so I make it my priority to try to help him figure out bills and other types of stuff to the best of my ability. I believe our children are a big reflection of how their raised, which is why it's important for me to make sure I'm doing as right as I possibly can.

I work a little more, have snack time, then it's my turn to take a shower. I let them play while I clean myself fast. Then I focus on chores. After chores it's lunch time, then nap time for my kids. I put them down for a nap, clean more, and relax for a few minutes. I wake them up, cook dinner, and then bath time. We relax, watch shows/nursery rhymes, and then it's bed time. I spend some time with my partner, and pass out. Over the weekend, we don't have the little ones, so I like to play video games and drink seltzers. This week was my daughter's birthday, so we broke from our usual routine. I kept her home from school, and my mother came to pick us up. We went to get a few birthday freebies I had found, and then drove to a different town to have pizza together. I also made her a special breakfast, as well as a lava cake in my crockpot.

ValuesSurvey:
The absolute most important value in life is honesty. I believe in dealing with people straight, and that if they ask me my true opinion, i won't lie, or obfuscate, to soften it. I do not volunteer mean things, I only give my opinion when asked. I believe this has earned me the respect of those people whom I respect. I believe it has also cost me friendships with those who are less than honorable in their words and deeds.

I would say that my next most important value is my compassion. I do not want to ever lose my compassion for others, as I feel this greatly informs my actions. It is better to be taken advantage of for this trait, than to not offer it. I feel too many people are closed off to the plight of others, and the world could be a much better place if we all just showed each other some more compassion. I feel exhibiting my honesty and compassion are who I truly want to be, and I do my best to demonstrate these in my everyday dealings and actions.

So, starting last Friday, we had an initial appointment and health screen at the vet, which was about an hour and a half long visit. That day also saw some interest in some items I had been trying to sell on Facebook marketplace, some fencing, and an old gate. I was lucky to sell both items, so taking Friday off was a win for me. I was able to get some Mturking in then, too. Saturday and Sunday were uneventful, but I did get to work out on Sunday ,and again on Wednesday. ValuesSurvey: For the past thirty years that I have been on this earth, I've learned about some values that I find very important to me. The first one is honesty, I feel that being honest so important. Trust is very valuable and not something that can be gained back if at all. Next is respect, I treat others how I would like to be treated. It doesn't always mean that I get treated with respect but, I think it has done more good than bad. I admire people that always try to be the bigger person. That's what I try to do in situations where there's a conflict or my patience is being tested. I also value self-discipline and strive for that in my life. It's very easy to get addicted to certain things like food or activities. Practicing self-discipline strengthens the mind. I believe that if you don't have any self-discipline at all, it's a huge weakness that should be worked on. Lastly, I value hard work and always believed in giving 110 percent in anything that I do. It's not always appreciated or noticed but it makes me feel good. I'm not perfect by a long shot but I'm trying. I'm always trying to make better choices and improving on any weaknesses that I might have.

ValuesSurvey: The most important values to me are those my parents taught to me, not just as a child, but throughout their lifetimes and my own. Of course the general golden rule one go without saying:  Be kind, be polite, respect others as well as yourself, do right by others, stand up and speak for or defend those who can't do so for themselves. One of the unique things that my parents share with my brother and I when we were young was to do four things each and every day to live a good life. 1) Do something kind for a total stranger. It could be something as simple as smiling and saying hello, or leaving a coin in a candy machine for the next child to find. 2) Do something kind for someone you love. Sometimes it would be do the dishes, laundry or lawnmowing even when it was not expected of you to help out a family member. Other times it could be offering a treat or favorite toy to a best friend, or spending time with elderly grandparents when you'd rather being playing with friends. 3) Do something kind for the world or our community. It could be picking up trash thrown beside a public trash can, or volunteering to help a local group or animal shelter. And last, 4) Do something kind for yourself. It could be use your allowance to buy your favorite candy, spend extra time doing your favorite activity, or just challenge any negative thoughts you've had. The key to the last one, my parents stressed, was that it was not enough to just "do" for others, you must also do for yourself. Those simple four things are something I still do 60 years later every single day, and I think most of my core values come from the mainstay of those four actions every day.

ValuesSurvey:
Integrity and groundedness.  

Telling the truth and learning how to navigate life with others in it have taught me that most often, at least for me, the cleanest and fastest outcome comes from telling the truth, and living that truth regardless of whether anyone sees it or acknowledges it.  This practice has led me to something more important over the years, and that's groundedness.  Being truthful to myself and others about everything, even if there are unfavorable consequences has allowed me to become more aware of my surroundings simply by being more aware of people and their feelings.  I have to see it, feel it, be part of it, and accept the good and the bad.

Just making people more "real" has afforded me the opportunity to pull my head out of abstractions and intangibles and remember that I'm on a little piece of the universe, surrounded by all of that infinite unknown in all directions, where I get to experience good weather, sunsets, trees blowing in the wind, cuddling, good food, and art. 

It comes with pain, but that's okay.  It's all part of it, and it's just as much part of it to make it as close to heaven on earth as possible by reducing that pain for each other.  

For me, that starts with just simply having integrity and showing people that I care enough about them to be honest and treat them with compassion.
BehaviorsSurvey:
Most of my days currently consist of taking care of my father.  As in, my days are the same for months at a time.  

My day starts with getting up and getting on MTurk to try and bring in any kind of supportive money to help while I spend all my time taking care of him.  I usually make breakfast after, then start the rest of my day, which is doing everything necessary to start my own business.  The past few years have been devoted exclusively to learning Adobe Suite products like Photoshop, Premiere Pro, and After Effects.  I'm currently taking courses on web design (HTML/CSS/Java) and have locally created most of my own website that I'm trying to finish up to get up and start making some passive income from.  Towards the end of the day, I exercise and shower, eat dinner, then hang out with friends online because it's the pandemic and I don't work and can't spend money anyway.

Although it doesn't seem like much, my activities total to 10-12 hours of work if not more, one hour for exercise if it wasn't taken up by work, then the rest is for myself or extra help for my father until bed.

ValuesSurvey:
I have what I call "The Pillars of Success in Life".

1. God
2. Health
3. Family
4. Friends
5. Hard Work
6. Interaction with The Natural World
7. Learning
8. Teaching
9. Giving
etc.

There are many but the ones listed above are some of the most important ones.

I use The Basic 3 Love Rule to guide everything I do.

1. Love God
2. Love Yourself - The humble type of love for self.
3. Love Others as you Love Yourself

I have practiced them and have realized that they come in that order. In other words, I must first Love God in order to Love Myself. I must Love God and Love Myself (the humble type) in order to Love Others as Love Myself.

These 3 Loves are very easy to understand and "to see". The hardest one, at least for me and for many people in my life, "Love Others as you Love Yourself" is by far The Hardest One of the 3 Loves. Very hard at times, especially for those we see as "Unlovable". 

After the 3 Loves, I think everything, including the 3 Loves, are based on Relationships. That is the key. We have relationships in our immediate and extended families, our neighbors, at school, at work, in our community, our Healthcare Providers, etc. Relationships are everything.

Now, Relationships are maintained and grow by communicating. Listening is the most important aspect of communicating. Most of us are really bad at listening. Especially active listening.

I also believe in interacting and taking care of the Natural World and all Living Things. Admiring them, respecting them, understanding that we are a part and not above The Natural World.  My parents have taught us that we must leave the world better than we found it. Improve it. Don't make it worse. 

Learning is a must and we all do it to some extent. But, teaching, or sharing what we learn is the next most important part of learning. Just learning is not enough. We can "hoard" knowledge and think we have the upper hand for doing so but no. It is actually the opposite. Because, others will not share their knowledge with us if we "hoard". And, more importantly, what we learned was written or said by others, for the most part. Also, teaching or sharing reinforces what we learn and makes it "stick". It also increases our Networks and keeps us more connected.

My oldest brother taught me, mostly through his actions, the 3 S's of money. 

1. Save Some
2. Share Some
3. Spend Some

With these 3, and in that order, we will have enough money. I can tell you that it works. I have seen it work in his life, in my life and in the lives of others in our circles. 

I value my Health and know it is a Gift from God and is not to be taken for granted. Health and Wellness make everything better and easier (not easy but easier). We should eat nutritiously, exercise daily, yes daily... even a 20 min walk is exercise. We should also stay connected and interact with God, people and The Natural World. All these things bring us and give us Health. 

Laughter is very important. It literally heals (Science has proven it). We must keep that "Childlike" aspect of our lives and have fun. As adults, we are very serious due to work, responsibilities, marriage, children etc. That is true. But we must have fun with those around us and always be willing and able to laugh.
BehaviorsSurvey:
These past 7 days I worked for 5 days in my regular job. It is very challenging and satisfying. Our work and the people we work with are "like our second family". Work and the relationships at work and belonging to a Big Group with a common cause brings me great satisfaction and identity.

I also go to the LA Fitness gym about 4-5 times week to do Cardio Workout, Lift Weights and to Play Basketball. I also socialize with my gym friends and acquaintances and with the gym Staff. The gym is a big stress reliever for me and brings me good Health. My connections and relationships at the gym are unique and "Athletic". We all have a common interest. Sports and being and staying in shape.

I also go to the local park with my girlfriend. We do this about 3-4 times a week and for about 45-60mins on weekdays and for about 1-1.5hrs on weekends. This is a great time to walk and talk outside with the trees and the wind around us. Really good way to see things from a different perspective. Our conversations are somewhat different when we "talk while we walk". It's one of our sayings..."talk while we walk". Very different than talking in the car, at home, in a restaurant etc.

I keep in touch with close friends and with extended family through Social Media, phone calls, facetime etc.  This is very important to me and I make time, even if it's just a 15-20 min phone call or a quick 5 min text.  I'm an Extra Extrovert and simply enjoy talking and interacting with people from All Walks of Life. 

Some of the Social Activities are limited now due to the Delta and Omicron Variants. This whole Pandemic that started around Feb 2020 has impacted All The World and has limited a lot of our Social Interactions, at least the physical ones. I have kept, we have kept an eye on the current Omicron Variant. About 90% of my immediate and extended family and my friends believe in The Pfizer and Moderna mRNA Vaccines. We are all fully vaccinated and in the process of getting our Boosters. We stay informed, share the info with one another, encourage each other and provide help finding Booster Shot locations, Appointments etc.

We are not discouraged and we don not live in a world of "doom and gloom". We simply stay informed, Trust but Verify the information and follow the Science. We are lucky to have some Doctors, Nurses and Pharmacists in our Extended Family. They bring perspective and give us another Opinion or more importantly, they summarize and "filter" some of the information.

I am looking forward to our Annual Family Christmas Gathering. Some will attend in person and others will be via Zoom/FaceTime. It's due to the Delta and Omicron Variant. It will be better than Christmas 2020 but not as good as Christmas 2019 and all those before that.

ValuesSurvey: I have several central and important values that guide my life.  I first value self-reflection and knowing myself.  I know that with all my flaws and judgments, I have a sense of self-awareness that I want to cultivate in my daily life so that I can become empowered to truly be aware of my thoughts and my actions, and thus be able to change things that don't serve me.  Engaging in daily meditation helps with this immensely.  To that end, I find that becoming less self-judgmental and more loving towards myself and others is a guiding principle that I want to incorporate more of in my life and interactions with others.  I also find that when I make decisions, I want to rely more on my intuition and gut-feeling, becoming aware of when something feels off or wrong versus right.  Getting into this space of awareness helps me become more empowered in making good decisions and positively impacting myself and those around me.

ValuesSurvey:
My core values as a person are to be the best mother I can possibly be and to be the best wife I can be. See I grew up with an alcoholic mother and a father that was never there for us. He was always out of town working. As I have gotten older and so has my child. I have learned things from being a child that have reminded me over and over again what to not be to my child. My parents were very abusive towards me and my siblings. Today I refuse to hit my child in anyway. Growing up back then versus growing up today is so different in so many ways. I know that I'm a great mother. I know this because my child isn't afraid of me. She isn't afraid for her well being. I do the best I can every single day for my child. I would do anything under this sun to give my child the live she deserves. I would even give my life to her, if it came down to it. 
Being a good wife. I have not always been good to my husband. I have done terrible things. Things he should hate me for. Things he should have walked away from. But he didn't. That man has stuck by me through my ugliest and my prettiest. And every since I did what I did, I have done everything in my power to make it up to him. I can't explain the feelings I have for my husband, we'd be here all day, but just know I can't live without this man. He has pulled me out of the worst of the worst mental states I have ever experienced. For that I own this man my life. I live everyday to do what I can to make him happy. I do everything I can, so he doesn't have to. I would walk through hell if I knew he didn't have to. I would also give my life for that man. He has loved me like no other person on this planet has. And let me tell you, I love him like no other on this planet. And I will continue to do so, till my last breath.
BehaviorsSurvey: A week ago today was Friday. So to start off I woke up and made myself a cup of coffee. After my coffee was done I proceeded to wake my daughter up and get her ready for school. After she was done getting ready for school and ate breakfast we were off to the bus stop. At the bus stop we talk about what she is going to do in school and how she is going to act at school. During the day, while she is at school, is when I get all my house chores done. My house chores consist of me taking the dog out 3 times a day, washing clothes for myself, my husband and my daughter, washing dishes, putting dishes away, cooking dinner, cleaning the floors, scooping the cat boxes, feeding the cats and if I have time, I try and squeeze a nap in there. When my daughter arrives home from school, me and her together will eat a snack out of her snack box. After she gets that done we start on homework. Her homework includes me and her reading either one or two books together and then she will take a test on the books that we read together. I will sit with her in case she needs any help. Normally she doesn't. But I am there if she needs me. After homework is done, me and her will start on our chores. At this specific time of day I know what I have to do and she knows what she has to do. So she goes on and does her thing, while I go and do my thing. After chores are done, I will start on dinner. While I'm cooking dinner I normally wash dishes as I dirty them from cooking. If my husband is home we will sit down together with no phones or electronics. But normally it's just me and my daughter. She prefers that we eat together but with electronics. So during this time, I will watch Netflix and she will watch YouTube. After we have ate our dinner we tend to sit there for awhile watching whatever it is we are watching. Mainly for our food to settle. Another because we don't really want to do anything else for the day. We've both had long and stressful day, so it's nice to just sit and watch something on our phones or tablets. But eventually we have to get back to reality and finish up our chores and get ready for the end of the day. The end of the day entails her taking a bath and me taking a shower. After that I put my daughter down in bed for the night. I usually finish up and chores I have not finished or gotten to for the day, while I wait for my husband to get home from work. When he gets home, I sit with him for a few hours and we talk about our day. How his day was at work and how my day was at home. After that I get myself ready for bed and my husband tucks me in for the night. I wake up the next morning and do it all over again. See I'm a stay at home mom, I don't get out much and I don't really have time for hobbies or interest. This is pretty much my every single day life.

ValuesSurvey: One of my core values is to do best not to judge. Have empathy. Although everyone judges to a certain degree, it is important not to let any preconceived judgements cloud your perception of who someone really is and their potential. I grew up abused and bullied due to being a bit different in things I liked, styles I enjoyed, and hobbies. It affected me for the rest of my life. In my earlier years, I coped with what happened to me by using drugs, which led to an addiction. I am now 4 years sober, and I often see how people at their lowest are judged. People look at me and see someone strong, but sometimes they don’t know my past and make comments about people who are just like how I used to be. It’s important to me to speak up for them, and show that everyone has value. Just because someone doesn’t fit your idea of a successful life, or doesn’t fit your religious checkpoints - they are not less than you. Everyone has value and potential, and until we as a society can openly take a look at what causes addiction and other behaviors society looks down on - we won’t ever be able to reduce it. Instead of looking at people as hopeless or wastes of life, people need to have some empathy and ask what got them to that point, and lend out a helping hand.

I got the news last Tuesday that a long time family friend passed away, so I sent my condolences to her daughter and got the funeral details so I can attend. Last Wednesday and Thursday we had a thunderstorm here in Minnesota, a rare thing to happen in December. It was followed by a first time ever occurance...extreme tornadoes, two of them, touching down in two different towns and causing much damage. Although we do get tornadoes in Minnesota in the summer, it has NEVER in recorded history happened in December. Today I will finished some house cleaning and then went to the grocery store.

ValuesSurvey: I have a personal relationship with God and that guides my moral life.  I follow God's principles as much as I can while not requiring anyone else to do so.  However, when interacting with people I do not apply God's principles because no one else does, even though they claim that they believe in God.  The only way to speak to people is to pretend that I am an atheist because they will not understand God's principals.  I will interact with people on what they think is morally right, even though it contradicts with God's principles.  Ironically people cannot even live by their own principles.  They would get mad if I point that out so it's no use trying to correct them.  I simply let them fail be their own fault.  It does not matter as long as I can get a job and support my family.

ValuesSurvey: For me, recently I found that one of the most important values of my life is my family. I didn't realize how important my family was to me until recently when my grandfather passed away and my grandmother moved away (rejecting the rest of her family). It made me realize how important family was to me. Not only that, but how important time also is. We are only here on this earth for a very short amount of time. We should spend every minute doing the things we love and spending time with the people we love. We aren't promised tomorrow and we should live every day like it's our last. Make sure to tell the people you love that you love them when you have the chance. Do you want to be remembered for your contributions to your work or how much you cared about those around you? These are the things that I have found to be the most important in how I live the rest of my life. I will continue to put effort into the things and people that matter most to me.

NO matter how bad it is, no matter what and you have my word" AND i mean it and anyone who has known me for a while and knows me for me knows that's the truth..And STILL when I know 100% without a doubt what the truth is this person will still look at me and lie right to my face. BehaviorsSurvey: My entire last seven days has not honestly been very exciting. ValuesSurvey: The most important values in my life are action over inaction and making sure I am not living life passively. For the first, I simply believe that it is one thing to hold a belief or to speak so easily about something but a more important next step is to really live those beliefs. For example, we hear a lot about being anti racist or pro environment and I know many people talk about how these beliefs are important to them but i'm more interested in how we can show these through organizing or community action or writing to local politicians about how these topics impact the community. I try to live my beliefs when I can and I know it's a huge privilege to be able to do so and not face repercussions on my job or my living situation. With work especially, diversity, equity, and inclusion are extremely important to me and I show up during meetings ready to discuss why these things are or are not happening in the spaces I take up.

ValuesSurvey:
My central values in life are to be comfortable and do as little harm as possible. Being comfortable is easy and, in the way I do it, makes doing less harm easier in many ways. As much as I love my work, it's not the center. My time is too precious for that, so I, and my spouse, aren't striving to be rich. I stay home a lot because that is a comfortable space. We both tend to keep to ourselves and maintain a mellow and relaxed home space. 

Reading and studying contribute to both my comfort and trying not to be a jerk. I enjoy both, but I also think that they help me to understand others better and to understand the impact of my actions better. I often encounter ideas and perspectives that I would not have found otherwise.

It's also easier not to do harm when I don't go out and around other people. I find it hard to understand what they want, and I'm definitely not the greatest at turning the other cheek. I'm not a particularly vengeful person-I won't hunt anyone down to get even or carry a grudge-but if you slap me, I'll slap you right back without thinking.

When I do get around folks, I do my best to try to recognize that they probably mean no harm. I also try to perform spontaneous acts of kindness when I can. Compliments, jokes, listening. Whatever I can think of that might put a smile on someone's face or make them feel good for a minute. 

In the end though, I'd just as soon be home with my books and spouse.
BehaviorsSurvey:
Last Saturday was unusual for me because I normally work on that day. However, I injured myself somehow and woke up in a lot of pain on that morning. As soon as it was a reasonable time of day to do so--I typically wake up between 6 and 7am, I contacted my boss. My right shoulder hurt so badly that even turning the pages of a book was unpleasant and painful. So I spent most of the day under a blanket with my arm propped up on a pillow to help stabilize it. I watched a LOT of TV since I couldn't do anything. I watched a play through of Resident Evil 2 from Leon's perspective, one episode of Star Trek: The Original Series, and then 6 episodes of Squid Game. I also very carefully stretched my arms at some point to ease the pain. I took ibuprofen throughout the day. 

Sunday, I felt better and didn't hurt, but I was carefully not to use the arm so as not to re-injure it. I studied and read most of the day. I studied both Thai and Spanish. I read from multiple books including The Portable Sixties Reader and The Blacktongue Thief. I also finished Squid Game because it was AMAZING.

Monday was another off day, and I was able to straighten up the house. As is typical of me, I studied both Thai and Spanish as well as reading through the variety of books I'm currently reading. I started a new audiobook that day, The Way of Kings by Brandon Sanderson. I also had a hearing aid cleaning appointment that afternoon, and after that, I treated myself to a poke bowl.

Tuesday was a work day, and it was pleasant and peaceful. I saw Rida on the bus in to work that day, and there was some excitement as a man, who was being nasty and abusive to the driver, had to be thrown off the bus. All the regular riders had a good time joking and gossiping about it after he was off. I enjoy my job and the company of my coworkers, so I typically like going to work. All of our patrons were pleasant, so while it was busy, I had a good day. I brought in homemade hot cocoa mix for all of my coworkers. Tuesdays are long for me so I typically go to bed within an hour of going home. Staying up long enough only to eat, prepare my clothes for the next day, and brush my teeth. I ate ratatoille (sp?) with Italian sausage as well as black beans and rice with sweet potatoes that day.

Wednesday was great. On Wednesdays, I get to see all of my coworkers and I love that. Our boss bought us delicious pizzas and salads that day. Additionally, two patrons brought us some boxes of candy and one of our coworkers brought a tasty Chex Mix. When I got home I relaxed with a tasty hot cocoa to which I added some Dark Rum. I read and chatted with my spouse and snuggled my cat.

Thursday as usual, I cleaned the whole house. I'm off that day, and I like to get everything done in one day if possible. I washed my laundry, cleaned the bathrooms, etc. I read and studied in between rounds of housework. I worked out at some point. I sent my husband the grocery list via text, and, as is our wont, he picked up pizza on the way home and we both curled up to eat pizza and watch British comedy. We are currently watching through all of the Would I Lie to You episodes. After that, we each relaxed in our own way (he games, I read).

Today, I have done little other than study and read so far.

ValuesSurvey:
My values: when I was 16 I almost died because I was put in a hospital to find out what my health problems were. They wanted to do one weeks worth's of test but they over dosed me on something they had given me, that I was already over dosed on. So, the one thing I would have regretted was, there were people in my life, I loved and I hadn't told them. So, when I got out of the hospital I let those I loved and cared about, that I loved them. That is my main guiding principle. So, I have lived my life, with gratitude for another day, letting those I love know. 
Other core values: be true to yourself, be honest, I am dependable, hard working. Treat people with respect. I believe GOD is in every human being and to treat all people fairly, respectfully and kindly. 
Try to walk through this life, without causing or occurring any karma. 
We may not be able to control what happens in our life but we can control how we react to things. So, that is one of the reasons, I meditate. 
I feel I have lived 3 lives: my childhood were I had health problems.
I learned to control and heal those health problems through natural methods: a good organic vegan diet, exercise, yoga and meditation. Then I had my work life: were I worked for others and then had my own business which I lost in 2008 financial downturn. I did my best but the economy changed and I accepted that. Then waiting to get to receiving early social security I was almost homeless. I was lucky and fortunate that a new friend let me rent her 2nd bedroom. I only had about $700 to my name. I had to get through 3 months and found a little job that helped me make it to social security. To me at my age: my spiritual life is more important to me now. I am looking not so much to the material side of things. Peace of mind, making a connection with that creative energy in all of us, whatever you want to call it: GOD etc. 
That is more important and helping were I can.
BehaviorsSurvey:
Last Friday, got up and did my normal routine: go to the bathroom, brush my hair and tie it in a pony tail, brush teeth, shower. Drink some water, do some exercises and stretching. Then I did my morning meditation on breath and such. Then I have 1 cup of blueberries, that have thawed, which I prep before my meditation. Then I turn on my computer and look at my emails, the news, check Mechanical Turk for possible HITs. Depending on the day, I might do some chores: getting RO water filled in 3 one gallon containers. On Friday my veggies and fruits are delivered from a local organic farm. They arrived early that Friday and I put them away. I started to make my lunch around 11AM. I have been making a winter soup: onions, ginger, garlic, a potato diced, couple of celery ribs chopped, a carrot diced, some cauliflower diced, broccoli diced and a shiitake mushroom. As it continues to cook, I add spices: tumeric, basil, thyme, sage.  After about 10 minutes we add some chopped cabbage or leafy green for a few more minutes. Then we take it off the burner and add: miso, tahini and about 2-3 TBSN of nutritional yeast. To this I will add 2 heaping spoonfuls of salsa. I take my vitamins before I have my lunch. I enjoy this soup and it keeps me in good health with a strong immune system. I may tweak a bit. After lunch, I check Mechanical Turk for HITs and try to meet my daily goal.  During the afternoon, I will check what is on my to do list for that day, check Youtube, get some chores done: take out the trash, read my current book, do some tasks for my local cooperative. I think I watched a movie on Roku last Friday. I usually stop eating for the day around 4PM. So, if I am hungry, I think I had a homemade Rubin Sandwich, which I love. I make my own wheat free bread, so I grabbed a couple of slices. I put about 1/4 package of tempeh in the oven for 10 minutes on one side and then turned it over for another 5 minutes. I had the bread toasting and took that out, put mustard on it, took the tempeh out of the oven and put that on the bread. I put a couple of slices of dill pickle on it and then topped it off with my homemade purple sauerkraut. Uhmm that was good eating, done before 4PM. I checked Mechanical Turk for HITs, then did some BrainIQ excercises to stay sharp and played some online Mahjongg games on AARP website.  When the sun starts to go I do another meditation for about 20 minutes. 
After that I check for possible HITs, check Youtube again and watch Glenn Kirschner each evening for his opinion regarding Trump's investigations etc.
I usually get some evening news items via my email, from people I trust for accurate news. Will watch some fun youtube videos till I start to get tired, which is around 9PM. Do one last meditation before I go to bed.
I have given you a pretty good idea what I did last Friday. My routine varies a little but that is about it.

ValuesSurvey: I think that in one sense, the most important value that guides my life is objectivity. The more I experience life, the more I seek to understand what is actually happening. What happens, happens. Objective reality doesn't depend on my mind to conceive it or to understand it. It just is. Admittedly, this value leads me to a place some would find ironic. It leads me to meditate often on Christianity, not as a political movement or a particular sect, although to be sure as a human person I count myself among a group of people who are, or seek, or claim to be like-minded. Rather, I meditate on Christianity as being the desire to imitate Christ. One of my favorite writers and opinion journalists typically writes about politics, but he occasionally has fascinating insights into faith. He has written about the need for Christians to understand that we believe audacious, implausible, radical things. That is undoubtedly true. But if I believe what I believe, I do it because I believe that Christ is the Nexus between humanity and the Divine. He is ultimate reality. His simultaneous humanity and Divinity simply are, whether I believe that or can understand it.

ValuesSurvey: The central value that guides my life is my belief in Jesus and following His teachings and virtues. I stated that it wasn't my thing, but the reality is that it was not to my taste because I believe in only presenting to my eyes and ears subjects that promote my values, not degrading/immoral/trashy/scary things that promote the devil's work. ValuesSurvey: A huge guiding factor in my life is if something will benefit or hurt me based on my actions or the decisions I make. Before I do or decide anything, I really take a step back and evaluate what it is that I am trying to accomplish. If its going to be beneficial in any way, I go ahead and decide for it. However, I also look into the future possible outcome of said decision. Its like a Yes or No algorithm scheme. I run through the scenarios that a decision might lead to, then what that will lead  to, and so on. This to me feels like the safest route. I do sometimes go with the flow, but I more likely than not think about my actions before I do them. I don't do it slowly either. I am able to process and internalize what is going on and fully understand what I want and want to accomplish.
BehaviorsSurvey: On Sunday I start my week. Its my Brazilian jiu-jitsu training day, and after I really feel like I am reborn. ValuesSurvey: I ask myself if the things I'm doing are healthy for both my mind and body. I want to be completely transparent with myself and those close to me because it's what I want from them. If I'm not honest with myself, how can I be honest with someone else? I want to be responsible and reliable in my everyday actions because, if I can't count on myself to do the right thing for myself and others, I would not be happy in my own skin. I need to trust both my action and their consequences. So, at the end of the day, I am happy with the person I am--my moral and conscious decision-making skills.
BehaviorsSurvey: During the past 7 days, because of Covid-19, my partner and I have spent time by ourselves. We greet the day with a special brew of coffee and talk about the day, as we watch the bunnies, birds, and squirrels munch on the food we put out in our backyard. After sitting, and watching the day start, we separate and go about our own tasks. I have done editing on my book of short stories, while he is either watching YouTube or fixing a household appliance. We then took a nice walk through the desert as it's warm enough to enjoy the wonderful views and sky! After our walk, we will again separate, and I worked on emails and communicating with my friends on Social Media. I did that for about an hour each day. Finally, we prepared our dinner meal together, with soft jazz playing in the background. We had chicken stir fry for 2 night, linguine with rocata cheese, dried tomato, and basil, sandwiches and soup, and home-made burritos.

ValuesSurvey:
One day, a man who I knew quite well, stopped me outside the library and told me that I was the MOST serious person he knew. I really didn't question him about his opinion of me, but I've spent considerable time over the last 15 years since that incident. 
I consider myself a pretty jovial person and light hearted but there what it made me do is look at those issues that I take VERY seriously.
Of those are, the treatment of those who are disadvantaged, whether it's related to race, gender identification, child/spousal abuse as well as other discriminatory practices.
I know that I can be very passionate when it come to child abuse and have started groups that discuss abuse and what we as a community can to do recognize it and to take action to keep if from happening. 
More recently with the killing of George Floyd and the BLM movement I have attended protests on the streets and have spent considerable amount of time bringing up issues/incidents on my Facebook page, and quite often stepping back and watching to see how others interact and often watching things turn into very heated debates. I often try to stay out of it, but at times almost have to step in as a referee. 
I tend to side with the ecology movement especially as it relates to our forests and oceans, and of climate change. Even though I'm of very simple means, I will take and contribute money to such organizations such as Green Peace and the Audubon Society. Being someone that is very at home in the out-of-doors in all four seasons, preservation of our environment is essential. 
I could go on..but I'll leave it at that.
BehaviorsSurvey:
For the past month, I have been living in an RV traveling along the west coast to where I currently am, in Tucson Arizona. I have typically start my day out reading email, posting to and replying to Facebook, and of course doing surveys on Mturk. 
During the day, either going shopping or going on hikes with our Golden Doodle or doing maintenance on the RV. 
Evenings are usually spent watching a show or two on the Discovery Channel. 
I think the most enjoyable thing we did was visit a very touristy community south of us, where my partner and I did some shopping and had a nice leisurely lunch.
At 67 life isn't quite as exciting as it was when I was younger, but I think I take just as much enjoyment in the smaller things in life.

ValuesSurvey: Really all my values boil down to "be kind".  As long as I am kind to others and do what I can to help out and show that I care to all of my friends then I feel that I have done my duty both as a human and as a friend.  There is no sense in being unkind to anyone no matter how you feel about their life choices.  Just be kind.  Everyone is equally human and no one can control what race/ gender/ sexual orientation they are born as.  So why waste any time being intentionally mean?  I mean sure I've had days where I have been less than.  I always go back and apologize and make up for my wrong doings and move on with those people I was unkind to.  I have a very good friend who I met online and he just came out as identifying as transgender and would prefer for everyone to refer to them as he/them.  So of course I agree and don't change the way I treat this friend.  Because even though I am referring to this friend as he now instead of she.  They are sill the same person who I knew before and as I stated before is a human deserving of kindness.
BehaviorsSurvey: In the past week I have not done very much.  I get up each morning around 10 AM and make my coffee and feed my cat.  Then I head back upstairs after saying good morning to my husband and start work for the day.  I work part time as an office manager for my Dad's business.  After I do my work for the day I head back downstairs to clean up the house a little bit.  This week though since Christmas is soon I've been making cookies and candies.  I've been thinking about trying to start a candy making business and sell candies either online or at fairs.  When I'm done for the day making cookies and candies this week I will usually sit in the living room and talk with my husband while he finishes up his day at work and play a game either on my phone or on our PS4.  I'll start making dinner after he is done at work, we'll eat together and then he goes to bed around 8 or 9 PM.  I then will go over to my computer room and play video games until about 3 AM.

ValuesSurvey: My central guiding values deride from Jesus Christ and my relationship with Him. As God incarnate, Jesus came to Earth to show the world what God the Father is truly like. The depth of His love compelled Him to sacrifice His life on the cross in order to atone for the sins of the world. That compels me to obey Him when He asks me to have compassion for others and tell them of God's love for them and the salvation available to them in Jesus. It also compels me to give charitably to those in need. The love of Christ plays the central role in all my decision-making; it forces me to consider and then act on what is best for me, for others, and for society in terms of furthering the Kingdom of God, since this world in temporal, and the Kingdom of God is eternal. Therefore, my over-arching goal is to persuade as many people as possible to accept Jesus as Savior and Lord and therefore become citizens of Heaven, and saved from eternity in Hell.

ValuesSurvey: I have a few important values that guide my life. I believe honesty is the best value anyone can have. No matter the situation, if you are honest it will be better than if you were to lie. Lying causes you to be caught up in different webs that you cannot get through once you create so many of them. I also believe in never judging anything by its cover. This applies to both people and aspects. I have had many relationships that have turned out amazing with people I would have never expected to like because of their cover. I have also had ideas instilled in me that I would have previously rejected if I had not dug deeper than the cover.
BehaviorsSurvey: Beginning a week ago, I got up in the morning like usual to wake my son up for school. He gets up and I help him get dressed and brush his teeth before he gets on the bus. Once he is on the bus I let my dogs out to use the bathroom and get started on making my coffee. I usually log into my computer after this and turn on the TV. I watch morning talk shows while I do my work. Around 2pm my son gets home from school. I help him do his homework and then begin battling laundry, dishes, and vacuuming before my husband gets home at 6pm. I cook dinner so that it is done by 7pm and after we eat whoever needs a shower takes one. By 8:30pm it is bedtime for everyone in the house. My weekdays always go this way and I have a pretty structured schedule to maximize efficiency.

Sometimes you personally need to do things that you don't want to but you know it will help you in the long run. ValuesSurvey: The values that guide my life are honesty, integrity, loyalty, and hard work. I feel like you have to be true to yourself and represent yourself honestly to others. This is the only way to find true acceptance and invite true acceptance into your life, to ultimately establish the kinds of relationships and find the kind of success (however that is defined) in life.  Treat others only as you want to be treated and expect nothing else. Hold yourself to high standards and don't compare yourself to others, which includes having expectations. Do if for yourself. Find true relationships and hold onto them and work to keep them. Understand what it means to be a real friend and know that the payoff is not superficial, but it is beyond that. Never act expecting returns.

ValuesSurvey: At this stage of my life, my values are centered on the Catholic Church and the Bible.  The top commandments are love of God and neighbor. So I try to do on to others as I'd have them do onto me.  That is respect their space and possessions, deal honestly with them, give when possible, try to be courteous in all events and pray for them whether I actually like them or not.  As Catholics we try to stay from sin as best we can.  Also, we are to be good stewards of what God has given us, so that means trying to take care of the planet and be as environmentally friendly as possible.  Also, I eat organic food which leaves far less of an imprint than conventional food does.

ValuesSurvey: My most important values in life are knowledge acquisition, hard work, and providing for my children. I also value things like honesty and helping others, but they are not guiding principles in my life. I am here to provide for my family and my children, not other people. It is not my job to take care of people who are less fortunate. I have been in the workforce since the age of 17 (13 if you count my newspaper delivery job when I was a kid), so I believe that hard work will get you where you need to go. I was raised with two mentally ill parents in a subsidized neighborhood, and my parents did not have much money. I made myself into what I am today, and because of that, I am entitled to what I have earned through my education and hard work. I am only obligated to share my accomplishments with my own family.

ValuesSurvey: I have a few basic, central, and important values in my life which influence how I interact with people and make decisions. From the interactions I've had in the past when I've been a little rude to people, and they still showed respect and politeness, really took to me. It made me feel better and that I shouldn't have been so rude. This made me realize how important this value is, as simple as it may seem. Another important value to me is honesty. Being honest is always the best approach to everything in life. It shows good character and that you can be relied upon.
BehaviorsSurvey: This past week was a little more hectic than other weeks, due to the fact that Christmas is right around the corner next week. Everyday as usual, I wake up and get a pot of coffee brewing before washing up to head out to work. I work in retail, so work for my has been filled with customers rushing to buy last minute gifts. I've been so tired from work, that I haven't really had the energy to do much this past week. I went to a Christmas craft festival to look for some small gifts that I could hand out to friends. It helped to brighten my mood and gave me a sense of relaxation. Other than that my week has been pretty mundane and routine. I will probably start packing today after work, to get ready for my trip home next week for the holidays.

ValuesSurvey: My most important values are my belief in showing everyone kindness even if they don't deserve it. I believe that if you show kindness to people who maybe aren't the nicest it might make them want to show kindness back. I also believe in being as friendly with people as possible so that I can have the best relationship possible with them. I especially feel this way about the people who I have working for me. If I can get along with them and they can get along with me it makes my day to day life so much better. It also helps people want to continue to work for me so that I don't have to spend a bunch of time hiring new people and trying to get them to fit into the team. Having honest relationships makes me feel more comfortable because I'm saying everything and anything that needs to be said. ValuesSurvey: The core value that guides my life is justice, in the sense of fairness. I highly value that everyone has the same opportunities, even if it means that some people get a lot more assistance in accessing those opportunities than others. I also believe it is important for each person to get the opportunities that suit them best, so if one person would prefer a career in skilled manual labour, that person should have access to quality training with an expert rather than being funneled into four-year college or something. I believe in a universal basic income and comprehensive healthcare for all. I believe in the inherent value and interconnectedness of all beings, so we must all care for and support one another. I believe in compassion and kindness above all. I value honesty, but only insofar as it is helpful.

Im not here to judge them simply help where and how I can. Sometimes that mean helping a person or waiting for cooler heads to prevail. Sometimes that means I need to face a wrong that I did by apologizing that I was mistaken or wrong.
BehaviorsSurvey:
I woke up sick, head full of junk, chest feeling like a small child was sitting on it. I rolled over and groaned, thinking, this is going to be fun. I called in sick. I called Quickcare and made myself presentable. 
After spending quality time in Quickcare I gathered my prescriptions and headed over to the local pharmacy. I felt terrible and waited as calmly as I could as kids coughed around me. Adults hacked into sleeves all around me. It was like a zombie horror movie, as I noticed more and more people sick at every turn. 
Was it that many? In truth most likely not. But it was a thought that traveled slowly across my addled brain. 
Once the drugs took effect the next couple of days were a routine; drugs, small amounts of food, lots and lots of liquids. Rinse. Repeat. Sleep filled most of my days as I recovered.

ValuesSurvey: One of the most important values is dedication to one's career/work. I believe this is important as this value informs how you approach both school and work, which will lead you to success and earning an income. This value is also important as it allows you to invest in one's passion, which is one's job typically. Another thing I value is financial responsibility. This is important as this is how you make sure your life functions smoothly, from saving for emergencies and retirement to having a house and a form of transportation. Another thing I value is making the most of free time. This is important as free time is a time to explore and learn about the world, develop your hobbies, and generally cultivate your interests outside of work. This makes the world interesting and provides additional meaning to one's life. These values allow you to meet the right people, care for those around you, and improve the lives of those who are engaged in similar passions as you.
BehaviorsSurvey: I wake up, check emails and texts and on my phone, then get up. I take a shower then get dressed for remote work. I then have a breakfast which consists of some fruit, and some nuts. I then work for a few hours on my computer at my desk. I then take a lunch break during which I eat some sort of sandwich with meat and a fruit to top it off. I then work for a few more hours. I might do a minor chore or two during the day if I have time. After work is completed in the late afternoon, I try to either get some form of exercise outdoors or run errands. If I am running errands, I usually walk to a nearby grocery store or bike to a store that might be farther away. I never drive to do errands as I do not have a car and I also do not take public transportation. For exercise, I either take a walk around the neighborhood, bike around town or on trails, play sports, or go to the gym where I lift weights. After these things are completed, I usually go home and have a healthy dinner then take a shower. I might browse the internet for a bit then go to bed. This has been my routine for the last seven days.

ValuesSurvey: In my life I try to focus on treating other people with respect and empathy. Everyone has their own ideas about life, what it important, how they should live, and how the world should work. I try to see their point of view, and even if we can't connect on certain issues, I try to be respectful and kind. We are all stuck on Earth, and there is no sense in being cruel to each other. I really want the best for humanity, and our planet, and the universe, and I try to contribute to that by not holding back the development of humanity by squabbling over petty differences. I also promote and participate in charities that provide education and basic needs so that more people can  thrive and contribute to society.

I got him a present, and cooked him dinner and a cake. I also deep cleaned the house that morning. Yesterday we bought a Christmas tree because his mom sent us ornaments, and we haven't had a tree in years since moving in together. I just finished decorating it this morning. I'm currently trying to get my cat to stop chewing it, and I'm thinking of wrapping the bottom of it in a fitted sheet at night when I can't watch him.

ValuesSurvey:
One of the main values to my life is honesty and sadly last year I did not live up to that standard. I was married for 8 years and then had an emotional affair with an ex girl friend. I have only ever cheated twice in my life and both times were with this girl. I can not say no. 

I tried to hide it for about a month and then finally had to come clean and tell my wife what was going on. Even though it was tough and hurt, I told my wife the whole truth, while it did lead to divorce, being honest is always the best thing a person can do. I wish I would have stuck to my values and told my ex wife what was wrong in our marriage and what I was feeling/thinking.

I wake up at 5 am and then take a pee, by 5:05 I am sitting in my chair and my wife is bringing me breakfast, I then eat breakfast and by 5:30 I am petting the cat good bye and kissing my wife as I walk out the door. I head down stairs and scrape the truck and then head to the bus barn. 

I drive bus from 5:45 to 8 am, and then park the bus and head into the school to shower. By 8:15 I am out of the shower and read to teach. I teach PE from 8:30 - 3:30. 

On Monday night there was a home basketball game that I went to until 10

On Tuesday night there was a school board meeting that I went to until 9

ValuesSurvey: I think one of my most basic values is honesty. No matter what the situation or what the outcome, honesty plays the biggest role as who I am as a person for many reasons. I want people to trust me, I want people to value my opinion and I want people to feel safe when they are with me. I think another basic value I have is empathy/compassion. I always try to find the good in people even if there really isn't any. I try to understand where they are coming from, even if it is not something I agree with. Another huge value for me is giving. Whether it's giving time, assistance or advise, I love to be able to give back to others. While I am not always in a position to give to places or people financially, I am often able to give in other ways.
BehaviorsSurvey: The past week has been fairly eventful. As we prepare for the upcoming Christmas holiday and wrap up school for my children for the year and finish up sports until the new year, hectic would be the first word that comes to mind to describe our week. Starting with Saturday, my day was spent driving several hours away to pick up my sons Christmas present up (he is getting a new KTM 85cc dirt bike). After picking that up, I headed to the outlet mall to make some smaller item purchases. I then went home, played with my kids and we went to bed. On Sunday, we picked up a friend and spent our afternoon at our local cities Christmas parade. While we enjoyed it, it was definitely geared towards younger children. From Monday through Friday, our days are fairly routine. We wake up, I drop the kids off at each of their schools, drive about an hour and a half to work, work and then leave work to pick them up. Monday evening, my son had wrestling practice and my daughter had basketball practice. Tuesday evening, my son had a wrestling tournament and my daughter had a basketball practice. Wednesday evening, my son had wrestling practice and afterwards we went to the store to pick up items we needed to prepare for my daughters school festivities on Thursday. We then spent our evening making finger sandwiches (ham & cheese, turkey & cheese and pb&j) and dirt cups (jello, oreos and gummy worms). Thursday evening, my son had wrestling practice and my daughter had basketball pictures as well as hitting lessons.

ValuesSurvey: My core values are authenticity, empathy, sustainability, kindness, and open-mindedness. These values guide every aspect of my daily life. They are equally important to me. Every word I speak, and every action I take is guided by these principles. Of course, I slip up sometimes. I am not perfect. For the most part, though, I try my very best to live these values and to practice what I preach. It makes me love myself, my friends & family, and the world more when I stand by my values. It helps me to become the best version of myself. My biggest goal in life is to affect positive change!
BehaviorsSurvey: Last Friday, I woke up feeling festive and decided to decorate the house for Christmas! After a delicious egg & cheese bagel sandwich breakfast, I took my furbabies for a walk. Then, I fed them, and got to work on the house. It was so much fun! Saturday & Sunday were spent relaxing with my husband. We played video games, cooked a lot of food together, and tidied up the house. Monday, I ate a hearty breakfast, took the dogs for a walk, then fed them. I spent the rest of the day working on microtasks for Amazon Mechanical Turk. Tuesday, Wednesday, & Thursday were spent the same way. Today, I woke up and went to our local food pantry. I got lots of fresh and canned food for Christmas! I was also given a live Christmas tree! It has been a great week, full of kindness, love, and relaxation!

ValuesSurvey: The most important things in my life are my faith and my family.  I am a Christian, so my Christian worldview impacts every decision I make.  What I do, how I speak to people, and how I act are all impacted by my faith.  In addition to my faith, my relationship with the members of my family is paramount.  I think about family all day every day and wonder how they are doing and how I can be of support to them.  I don't mean to imply that I don't have my own life and I do pursue my own interests, but family opinion and support is what I value the most.
BehaviorsSurvey:
Last week I was on vacation in Hawaii.  I had a great time and spent most of my time lying around the pool area, swimming in the ocean and walking along the beach.  We did go out on a boat trip that included snorkeling.  That was so much fun and we were able to see marine life that I had never encountered before.  Following the boat ride we stopped for lunch at a restaurant that is famous for their mai tai's.  They were fantastic.

Once the vacation ended, it took me almost an entire day to get home.  I had multiple layovers in various airports and spent most of my time there walking up and down the concourses trying to keep myself awake as well as get some exercise.  

Now I am home and life has settled back into my normal routine of up early at 4:45 AM to walk 5 miles, then work, then home to spend time with my husband and dogs.

ValuesSurvey: The most important and influential thing in my life is when I accepted Jesus Christ as my Savior and Lord.  I was young at the time, but I knew I needed to have a relationship with God and that I could.  I was raised in a Christian home and my values and guiding principles come from having an active faith in Christ.  I get my values from the Bible.  That is why I am against abortion, etc.  I had an eight-year-old son who was diagnosed with bone cancer.  For almost two years he fought and struggled with it.  He had an amputation of his left leg, two lung surgeries, and at least a year of chemo.  Through it all, he kept a happy disposition.  He could find joy in life.  When a newspaper reporter asked him how he could be so happy, he replied, "I know that Jesus will never leave or forsake me."  He died peacefully at the age of 10.  That is the kind of peace and faith Jesus gives us.  He has promised to never leave us.  Although I don't understand all the hard things people go through and the difficult things in life, I can trust that God is sovereign and will make everything right soon.
BehaviorsSurvey:
I can't remember too well what I did on Friday and Saturday of last week.  Probably the typical day-to-day type of things--getting up and dressed, eating breakfast, checking email, doing MTurk, fixing lunch, doing dishes, maybe going to the store, etc.  
On Sunday we drove half an hour to the church where I taught the Senior Ladies Bible Study class and then attended the church service with my husband.  After church, we had a Women's Ministry meeting where we ate lunch and discussed the issues of our Ministry to Women.  After that, we drove home and I caught up on my computer items and did daily chores and routines.  Several times this week we went to the store to get items we needed.  On Tuesday, after doctor's appointments and errands, we drove to KC to check on a car we wanted to buy.  We were there early and waited to meet him.  We ended up buying the car and I had to drive one car home, following my husband.  That was grueling!  I hate to drive, it was at night and there was a lot of traffic.  But we made it home.  On Wednesday we had an appointment with the Pest Control to put out bait boxes for mice.  On Thursday we received a portable dishwasher that we had ordered.  It was a very busy week.

ValuesSurvey: The most fundamental value that guides me is integrity. This stands as the basis for all of my other values, because without I could give up on my other values. It is to upmost importance to me that I am true to myself and adhere to my beliefs. There was a time in my life when I would maybe go against who I was, even if just for a moment, to be accepted or not stand out. Those days are surely behind me. When I think of all the times I wasn't true to myself, I never want to be like that again. Staying true to not only myself, but to the ethics and morals that govern my way of life have never been more important to me. Fairness is at the base of my values when interacting with others. I know what it feels like and means to be treated unfairly and I don't want anyone to ever feel like I am doing that to them. I put in as much effort as I can to be fair to anyone I am interacting with. There was a time when being fair wasn't as important to me as it is now. I don't remember too much about that time, but I do remember that when I started to feel I was being treated unfairly I didn't want anyone to feel that from me. I wanted to be somebody who took everyone into consideration and be aware of their unique situation. Whatever it may be. I would say those are the most important values that I hold the closest to my heart and am not willing to compromise.

ValuesSurvey:
Something that I will always live by is to treat others how I would want myself to be treated, although it is not always clear to me. I remember this principle because whenever I am not sure how I feel about someone, I try to think through and imagine how I'd want to be treated if I was in their place, and go from there. It's helped me throughout life to just stop and think before making decisions, even if they are everyday decisions. I believe that a person's habits really determine who they are, so I try to implement this in my every day life to make these behaviors habitual for myself. 

For example, I have had friends who were too afraid to tell me how they really feel about certain things, and it has only made things harder. The best thing to do is to just be straight forward without loosing control of your emotions.

One rejected me due to a better candidate but I am still waiting on the other. Rest of the week I did work related to my stock market positions and shoe business.

ValuesSurvey: The most important values that guide my life are honesty, loyalty, trust, fairness and virtue. I value honesty because it helps people to communicate with each other better. When people communicate, there are fewer misunderstandings. I also think society and relationships cannot function without people being honest. I also value loyalty. Loyalty is important in a relationship because we need to know someone will be there for us when times are bad. I want to know that I can trust someone to take care of things. Fairness in life is important because everyone should be able to share in the earth's riches equally. Virtue is important in relationships because society cannot function when people have low moral standards. The world would erupt into chaos without all of these values being followed by people.
