ValuesSurvey:
My most important values can be synthesized into one: being true to myself at all times. 

I'm at an age now where I'm able to be honest with myself and accept myself, flaws and all. So that's how I approach life. 

I realize what other people think of me is none of my business, nor my concern. I focus on how I feel about myself. And I strive to be a better version of myself each day for myself, not approval from others.

I want to be kind to myself and others and accept that I'm not perfect, and neither is anyone else. We're all flawed. And I think that's made life a lot easier for me.
BehaviorsSurvey: During the past seven days, I've been working, reading, writing and returning e-mail, spending time with loved ones, listening to music, playing video games, cooking, housekeeping and meditating.

ValuesSurvey: One of the central and most important values that guides my like is peoples' right to privacy. It is for that reason that I will not be discussing my other values at this time, because even though my identity is protected information for this study, I do not know where the written contents may appear or be quoted, and so this information could potentially be used to identify me. Being able to choose what to reveal about oneself is as important as being able to wear clothing in public. It is as important as being able to decline strip searches. We all deserve the right to choose what to share.

ValuesSurvey: The central and most important values that define my life are kindness, and a concept of "live and let live," as long as it's not hurting anyone or anything around you.   My deepest thoughts are about being empathetic, kind, compassionate and generous with my caring for others.  This includes animals and the environment.   To make difficult decisions, I use my spiritual Christian based guiding principals.  I try to think of what adheres to my morals and ethics based on what I believe in.  I try to remember to live well, speak well, not judge others and to forgive others.  I try to interact with people in pure kindness without judgement on their situation.  These values in relation to who I am?  Kindness, non judgement and empathy--  I try to look at everyone through their own eyes. I try to find the best in people and interact with them like I would want people to treat me.  I try to extend to others anything and everything that I would want extended to me.

I did not leave the house once in the past week.  My car has been broken down and I have had to get grocery delivery. ValuesSurvey: My three most core values would be intelligence, compassion, and fun; if someone doesn't show all of these I will most likely not like them as a person.  For intelligence I can not stand an anti-vaxxer, science denier, or someone so idiotic that they believe JFK is going to return to life.  For compassion, I want to help those in need at any cost, as long as people are homeless, going hungry, or struggling to survive, we as a country aren't doing our job.  If I see someone miss treating someone, looking down on someone, or treating someone like a lesser human, it infuriates me and I will very likely step in.  Finally for fun, I believe that people put too much emphasis on work, some people make it the center of their life.  If they enjoy it then that's fine, more power to you; but to me work is work.  It is not the center of my life, and I find it sad that so many people devote their life to a company or business that doesn't care about them at all.  I want to be me, I want to do things for me, and as long as the bills are paid, I would rather the rest of my life to be filled with fun things.

After I finish work I either play my Nintendo Switch or my PC games for most of the night with my girlfriend.  I cook dinner maybe twice a week for us, I specialize in cooking Kung Pow Chicken. ValuesSurvey: The largest moral principle by which I live my life is to do as little harm to others as possible. I believe the world and life, in general, are already very cruel. We cannot readily predict when we will encounter suffering and, more often than not, we cannot tell if another person is currently suffering. In my life, I feel I have experienced an exponential amount of suffering, more than everybody I know, so I understand what its like to suffer in silence. Due to the unpredictability of the things that hurt us in life, I prioritize not being something that hurts others. I try to be as kind and considerate as I kind. I go out of my way to help others and make them feel joy if I can. This spreads to most of my other philosophies as well.

ValuesSurvey: My most central values revolve around kindness and survival. My childhood was really rough; I came from a house where I was abused in every way, and I witnessed an insane amount of domestic violence, crime, pain, and mistreatment. I decided early on that I was going to live a GOOD life — I was going to survive this, get out, and be happy. Aside from a huge amount of PTSD, I have mostly managed it — in the simplest terms, I formed my values by just doing the exact opposite of EVERYTHING that was modeled to me in my childhood, but more expansively, I’ve focused on happiness and kindness. I treat people the way I want to be treated (kindness), unless they treat me badly, and then I draw a hard boundary and I simply refuse to have anything to do with them (survival.) Obviously there are exceptions — coworkers that I cannot simply avoid, things like that — but by entering the world with both kindness and boundaries, I’ve been able to navigate most things successfully. I have struggles and hard days, but the gradual curve of my life has been upward since I left home, which is a huge deal — statistically, women from backgrounds like mine often recreate them, falling victim to domestic violence, addiction, murder, or suicide in adulthood, and Im living a life NOTHING like that. The other thing that has been a powerful force in defining my values (and I’m treating my PTSD) has been Buddhism — simple states, trying my best to stay in the now as much as possible.

I was congested and sore and miserable. Friday was the same way. On Saturday the antibiotics caught up and I was able to get out of bed, which was great — we have children who are only half way through their vaccinations, so we’re still staying home and safe most of the time, so we spent Saturday and Sunday hanging out, playing board games, watching movies, cleaning, and relaxing. I also spent a lot of time unpacking our last boxes — we moved here to a new house a couple of months ago and I’m still unpacking the last handful of random small boxes. Monday I did homeschool with my kids while my husband worked from our home office; that was the same thing we every weekday this week. We have a fairly structured weekday schedule because of home school and work.

ValuesSurvey: The values I hold in my life that are central, especially in raising children, are those of honesty and putting your best foot forward at all times. I don't care if my children struggle with school, grades, etc. I simply want to know that they are being honest about doing their homework and trying their hardest to make the grade. I want them to tell me if they have been in trouble or done something wrong before I find out from someone else. I try and model these behaviors but I also try to model being humble and admitting when we fall short. I don't always do my best and sometimes we are just tired and overwhelmed. I want to be able to be honest about that and I want them to too.

ValuesSurvey:
My most important value is FREEDOM. There are many ways to look at freedom, and the most important of these for me is the physical ability to relocate away from a place that I do not want to be. 
That's why I thought my world had ended when states began mandating that, as the price of transportation, I surrender the ability to get up from a seat for the duration of my time in a car (with the Damoclean sword of maybe not getting it back after the duration). this  has been followed by surrendering the right to even adjust the degree of my confinement. Now, even the decision to get out of the car can't be made without the permission of the car itself.
This has blossomed into an acute awareness of how deeply Government entwines itself into people's lives for the benefit of a select elite with no recourse for the "working stiffs"

ValuesSurvey: I suppose I have to start with the fact that I'm a liberal.  So, my core and basic values inevitably come back to that.  Think about your typical bleeding-heart liberal, and that's me. I believe in family, despite my shrinking one.  I believe in the American justice system, as flawed as it is.  I am for helping the poor and taxing the rich.  I am for affordable college, affordable groceries, and not tempting people to trample each other on black Friday.  I am definitely concerned about our environment and what we're collectively doing to this planet.  I try to do my part to the best of my abilities, but we just cannot leave this planet the way my generation found it.

ValuesSurvey: The most important values that guide my life are adventure, knowledge, change, and family. As a queer woman coming from a pretty religious, misogynistic, and paternal family it is important that I achieve my dreams and that those dreams are outside the normal societal expectations. I have already traveled to more countries than anyone in my family ever has. I have been to all 6 continents and lived in New York City. Achieving this when all that was expected of me was to marry a man and have children and never leave my hometown, is very important. I continue to strive for change and adventure and will always do so. I also try to make a point of spending extended time with my elderly parents as much as possible because I know this time will be extremely important to me someday when they are gone.
BehaviorsSurvey: Starting on Friday, December 10, I began a drive from California to New Mexico. It was a 13 hour drive. I stopped for gas a couple times and to eat lunch at Subway. I arrived at 10pm in New Mexico. On the 11th I spent the day with my New Mexico family. We drove around Santa Fe, ate brunch, got hot chocolate, and then went to their home to chat and make pizza for dinner. On the 12th we went to a arts and crafts festival in Santa Fe where my family sold their crafts. We were there all day. I bought some crafts. We went for dinner afterwards. On the 13th I drove from New Mexico to Texas. It took 9 hours with a couple stops for gas and lunch at Wendy's. On the 14th I watched TV and read and then met my family for dinner at a tamale restaurant. On the 15th I had a phone call with my best friend for two hours. Then I watched TV and read and had dinner. On the 16th I went to see a movie with a friend of mine at the theater. Later that night a family member came over for dinner and we chatted. I ended the night with a Christmas movie. Today I have watched TV and ate lunch so far.

ValuesSurvey: The one guiding value... well, two guiding values that define who I am is being straightforward and honest when it comes to anyone I talk to or end up meeting regardless of the situation. I came to value this when I learned the hard way that lying only leads to more lies until someone ends up getting unintentionally (or intentionally) hurt in the process... plus I wasn't really a very good liar to begin with. Since those days when I was younger, I've really come to value when someone or something is being honest and straight to the point. It's a value that my family holds in high esteem as well, seeing as how they tend to practice it in their daily lives to the point where it is about as natural as breathing. Another thing I value is kindness, considering that I do my best to come across as that to those who are in need of that metaphorical light in their lives. There's far too many instances where people tend to close themselves off because of what they've been through, and the reasons are understandable... but after a while, one longs for some form of companionship, and it never hurts to start with meeting someone halfway who also wants a similar thing.
BehaviorsSurvey: For the past seven or so days, I've just been going about a regular routine... or about as regular as it can be given the condition of the world that's still ongoing as I'm typing this. I usually wake up in the morning and start staring at the ceiling while contemplating on what I could do or get done today, and it also doubles as a means of getting rid of that half-asleep feeling. After that, I get out of bed and stretch my arms and legs before immediately opening up my laptop to continue what I was doing or watching the day prior to this next one. What I usually end up watching on YouTube is either video game things, stuff on old technology, old commercials that really get me reminiscing, or cooking in case I was feeling really hungry and waiting for some food to be heated up or made. Related to the video game stuff, it's usually reviews of games I already have or am currently interested in buying and just wanting a second opinion on whether it would be worth the investment.

ValuesSurvey: More and more I find my main and most basic values revolve around not allowing this sometimes crazy world to make me act crazy. Particularly with national politics and everything seeming to get more extreme, I refuse to allow things to make me become more extreme. I believe extremism is childish and lazy. It also creates conspiracy theories, which are the antithesis of trying to live a reality based life. The far left and far right live in a fantasyland that I want no part of. I teach my children that extremism is not the virtue the extremes pretend it is, that maturity is dealing with reality. I also teach my children they are no better than anyone else and to treat everyone accordingly and to not stoop to the hatred spewed by so many.

Also feed the dog and take him out. My husband is pretty self sufficient so besides making him breakfast sometimes, I don't have to worry too much about him. I also shower and dress in between all this before driving the kids to school and driving myself to work. I work all day, meeting with coworkers sometimes and sometimes working alone. I often take a lunch break to go take the dog out and eat quickly. At the end of the work day I sometimes run errands or pick the kids up from after school activities before heading home to make dinner, make sure homework is done, watch some tv, and get everyone ready for bed before starting all over again. Our weekends have a lot of activities with the kids, for example we went to the beach on Saturday. And my son had a tee ball game on Sunday.

ValuesSurvey:
The central and most important values that guide my life are truth and compassion.  Truth is the most central value since it is the foundation for all of existence.  Anything untrue is not real, and is therefore illusory and actually non-existent.  The relative human experience is contained within Truth.

Compassion is the most important value in this relative human experience.  Care and concern for your fellow beings and environment is not only critical for a life well-lived, but it is vital for survival itself.

ValuesSurvey:
Ultimately my guiding principle comes from my belief in God. I try to live selflessly and love and serve others. I don't want to just live for my own comfort and pleasure. However, I often find myself living for myself. 

I recognize that life is temporary. Getting physical possessions is not as meaningful as helping someone else, so I want to live in a way that makes other people's lives better, not just my own.

This means we try to give to others and invite people over to spend quality time with others, rather than just living our own private, separate lives.

I am always looking opportunities for the "next right thing" and I pray for how my life should go.

I try to love and serve my wife as well, so I am working to make sure the way I live does not sacrifice my relationship with my family.

ValuesSurvey: One of my most important values is integrity. I find it the most important because of how it impacts so many behaviors and actions in your life. Living with integrity allows me to feel confident in how I treat others and ensure that I feel good about my actions at the end of the day. I think that compassion comes in a close second. Compassion allows me to assist others in ways that I may not have considered and will propel my opportunities to put goodness in the world. I think both of these values are important because of how much we interact with people around us and the impact we have on their lives. Living with both of these values means that each person I interact with can walk away feeling positive and happy. I enjoy making sure that I am honest with each of these to ensure I live by my moral code.  Each of these three moral principles requires constantly checking in with myself to ensure that I am following them and making the best decisions available to others and myself.

ValuesSurvey:
One of my central beliefs is that people must be dealt with consistently and fairly. I don't like the idea of engaging with people on the basis of preconceived notions of who that might be because of what group to which they might belong. When I meet a person, I am first and foremost meeting a fellow human being. The process of understanding that human being might be shaped by previous experience, but understanding can never be solely determined by previous experience.
I also believe that coercion of other people must be kept to a minimum. There are essential human rights with regard to self-determination of religion, speech, social attachment, etc.
I also believe that a fundamental good is obtained by helping other human beings. This is not always easy given the other values that I mentioned previously: There have been many well-intentioned people in the past who have tried to "help" others and who in so doing either violated the rights of others or who engaged in some form of patronization which pushed their own shortcomings onto others disguised as gifts.
I can only understand myself and grow if I allow others to come into my life and assist me in my growth. It is important to maintain one's sense of independence and individuality, but if that sense of independence becomes all-important, then I will become permanently isolated and "stuck."
BehaviorsSurvey:
Last Friday through Tuesday, I worked the late evening to early morning shifts at the grocery store at which I work. My life on work days is quite regular: I awake from sleep sometime between 11 a.m. and 1 p.m. I prepare myself a cup of coffee and look at the news online and also look at Facebook to see what is happening with my friends and family. As a diversion, I play the game Scrabble Go on my handset. I invest in a variety of stocks and funds, so I often spend some time each day investigating market news and information. About two hours before my work day is to begin, I begin to prepare myself mentally for the workday ahead. I am a cashier at a grocery store. Retail is a difficult area in which to work at the present time owing to the increasingly poor public behavior evidenced by many. So I steel myself for the day by preparing myself mentally for what I might encounter, and by making myself as physically comfortable as possible. I make sure my body is well-hydrated and that I feel clean and comfortable before going to work. When I am at work, I try to concentrate on doing my job as effectively as possible. I try to be positive and upbeat with customers as much as I can. I am sympathetic and try to be helpful to both my coworkers and customers. I work hard at a job which is often repetitive and mentally unrewarding.
Once I drive home from work, I try to unwind and let the other parts of my mind find time to function. I am very interested in history and archaeology of late, so I often find videos on Youtube which relate to these topics. I also enjoy Scrabble, so I play Scrabble Go on my phone quite a bit.
I live in the snow belt, and last Friday we received our first major snowstorm of the year. I rent an upstairs suite of rooms with 3 other people and we are responsible for shoveling parts of the property. So, last Saturday I spent 2 1/2 hours shoveling snow. It is an activity I have engaged in for many years and I am actually quite fond of it. There is a sense of accomplishment to being able to look back at a cleared walkway or path after having shoveled it, remembering that only a short while earlier it had been a small sea of whiteness.
During my days off, I like to engage in long walks. This past Tuesday and Wednesday were consecutive days off for me, a rarity of late. On Tuesday I took a long walk and after it went to an Asian-themed grocery and purchased a prepared meal from its deli. This is a luxury for me. 
I also spend a good bit of time investigating my ancestry. I have taken a DNA test and assembled a family tree on a popular genealogical website. I try to review as many hints and do research as much as I can.

ValuesSurvey: The most important values in my life are respect for all life, inner peace, and humility. In my life, there are have been times that I have truly exceled at following these values, and other times that I have fell short. I will go through each of these values in more detail. As far as respect for all life goes, I feel that in all of my life decisions, I try to determine how other lives were or are impacted by my decisions. For example, I try to eat a vegetarian diet, and most of the time, eat completely plant-based. I do this because I know that animals that are sent to slaughter houses are not treated with dignity and respect in their last moments. By purchasing the meat, it means that I am supporting this behavior, and therefore am not displaying respect for the innocent animals that have been slaughtered. I also try to think of environmental impacts when I make decisions about what to buy. For example, before I buy anything, I always ask myself if it is something I can do without, something I can make, or something that I can buy used. Only if the answer is no to all of those questions do I buy something new. When I do buy goods, I try to buy as local as possible because it means less transport and therefore less carbon emissions. Inner peace is a value of mine because I feel that when I have inner peace, I can then emit that peaceful energy to others in my life. When I have inner peace, I am at my absolute best. I have infinite patience for my family, I make good decisions with my own life, and I don't do things like speed when I drive or honk my horn when I am annoyed at other drivers. I also find that I don't compare myself to others. I am just at peace in every way. Lastly, humility. Knowing my place in the universe is so incredibly tiny, spontaneous, and unlikely keeps me in check. My problems are so miniscule compared to many others, and also compared to the great expanse of the universe. Having the mindset that I am just a tiny speck of dust on a tiny blue dot floating in space keeps me humble and treating others with the utmost respect, and giving others my full attention.
BehaviorsSurvey:
Things that I have done in the last seven days. Probably the easiest way to do this in separate paragraphs, organized by different types of activities. I know this deviates a bit from the organization suggested above, but I feel like it is the only way I can do it. 

Once a week activities: I baked two loafs of whole wheat bread on Tuesday, and froze one of the loafs for use later. I also worked on planning my vegetable garden for the next season, and started a list for ordering from the seed catalog. In addition, I cleaned all the windows of the house, cleaned the bathroom, and meal planned for the week. I also grocery shopped. I also dropped off the rest of the Christmas cards to the post office. 

A few times a week activities: Every other day, I catch up on laundry, so each of those days I do at least one load of laundry. I also sweep every room in the house and vacuum all of the carpets. I try to work out a few times a week, so this week I did three days of calisthenics and squats. I also cleaned out the refrigerator a few times and organized the pantry. It gets messy quick with little kids around. 

Every day activities: I cook breakfast, lunch and dinner every single day for my family. My husband works outside the home during the week, but I am home to cook for my son every day. I also do the dishes every night, and clean the dishwasher out every morning. I check the mail, take my son to the park, and play in the backyard with him every day. I drink coffee every day, and feed and take my dog out to potty every day. I sit and drink tea and read every night, and have at least an hour of alone time with my husband every night after our child goes to sleep.

ValuesSurvey: I use the Bible, prayer, and the Holy Spirit to make the most important decisions and to guide my values in life. When it comes it difficult decisions there is only one guidebook to life that I know to be accurate and true: the Bible. I can go to it for answers for anything that I may have questions about. There is literally nothing new under the sun and nothing that cannot be solved by searching through the scriptures. I also depend on prayer and communication with God through the Holy Spirit to make my decisions. He is my guide and I can count on answers from Him that are correct and true when I have an important decision to make. These same values are shared with the people who are most important in my life as well.
BehaviorsSurvey: Since last Friday I have been to practice for Christmas Cantata, baked cookies, baked bread, made dinners, done laundry, written three thank you notes, anonymously sent gifts cards to a person in need, called to cancel reservations at a hotel, made reservations at an Airbnb for next April's vacation, texted with my mom and sister, wrapped presents, watered the Christmas tree, vacuumed the floor, cleaned the bathroom, made copies for a meeting, attended a business meeting, taught a Bible study, completed an Advent Bible study, finished a book, made a phone call, delivered Christmas goodies to three different people, shopped for groceries, researched how to make a Hot Cocoa Bar.

ValuesSurvey:
My most distinctive characteristic is my independence and originality.  I didn't have much of a family and was never "raised" in any particular way.  If I learned anything in youth it was to be distrustful of authority figures and only rely upon myself.  I have carried this belief with me into and through adulthood.

My values have changed over time.  I have become extremely egalitarian and politically active.  I find the United States government to be absolutely abhorrent in nearly every respect, regardless of which of the two major parties is in power.   One of my guiding principles is to elevate meritocracy above privilege or aristocracy.   We seem to live in a sort of kakistocracy, ruled by an absurd and indolent caste of unweaned adult sucklings who could not even pay their own rent as young adults, yet somehow presume the standing to opine on such things as whether or not this person or that person should receive health care.  

I think community is important but I am not a particularly social or sociable person.  Probably this is something I should work on in the remainder of my allotted time on our planet.
BehaviorsSurvey:
A week ago I was talking to my dear friend who recently left the hospital.  She had a mysterious illness that worried us quite a lot, and her condition is still perplexing.  It worries me a great deal.

Last weekend I relaxed at home.  Usually this involves playing video games, watching the Cleveland Browns, and playing chess online against some of the country's best rated tournament players.  I say this because I have no specific memory of doing any of those things.  I don't even remember which team the Browns played --- and yet I'm sure that they played and that I watched them.  Curious.

At work this week I was mostly involved with a new project, which is to install a customer relations management software.  The seller has a team to help us with that but their assistance is promised for only the remainder of the month.  We're operating under a deadline. 

I also have some routine tasks at work; e.g., managing my six employees, meeting with the occasional client.  On Wednesday I traveled downtown to meet with a judge and opposing counsel on a criminal case.  But the rest of the week I remained in the office.

ValuesSurvey: The most important values that guide my life are my family, my religion and myself.  My family is there to point me in the right direction.  They are there to tell me what is right and what is wrong.  My religion guides my spiritual path.  As for me, I am the sole factor of my decisions.  Ultimately, I am the one who decides my faith.

I believe it was mid-week after taking exams.  I really needed that break before finishing off the week of classes.

ValuesSurvey: One value that is very important to me is to take care of the people I care about. By extension, that includes animals as well. My girlfriend and I have three cats and a dog. To take care of them, and my girlfriend, and to just survive in this capitalistic society, I have to work full time so I can afford shelter and food for myself and everyone else. That's why most of my days are taken up by my job. I also care deeply about my health, which is why I go to the gym most days of the week. Exercise has been proven to better pretty much every aspect of health. Plus, I just like doing it.
BehaviorsSurvey: There isn't a lot of variety in my typical week since I am a product of a capitalistic society. Pretty much any given day (Sundays are my only guaranteed day off), I wake up around 5:30 am and make myself breakfast, usually bread with peanut butter if I'm still tired, or pancakes. I eat breakfast, and then spend a little bit of time with my girlfriend before she goes to work. I then go to the gym at about 6:30 or 7 am, and stay there until around 8:15-8:30 am. I get home, change, make a protein shake, and play with my dog for a little, and then I go to work. My work day starts at 9am and I get off at 6pm. Once I get home, I make dinner while my girlfriend and I tell each other about our days. We eat dinner, and then relax on the couch for a little watching whatever  we feel like watching on TV that night. At around 8pm, I take the dog for a walk. When I get home, I usually do the dishes for the day, and then we go to our rooms and get ready for bed. I usually spend about a half an hour playing with the cats, then I shower, brush my teeth, and then go to sleep. I wake up the next day and do the same thing.

ValuesSurvey: The most important values in my life are putting family first and living a genuine life. That means being kind and honest towards people, and valuing the people closest to me. The things that guide those principles are my upbringing by my parents, and my religious background as a christian. My parents instilled in me the importance of honesty and kindness, and that your family will always be there to support you when you need them. Honesty is important because it is important that people value and trust your words and your actions.

ValuesSurvey: The most important values in my life are those that define me as an individual. By this I mean the things that I am and I want to be. So, specifically, this is being intelligent and analytical, being fair, being intellectual, being innovative and wanting to try new things, being artistic, and being active. I try to evaluate difficult situations by finding the actions that best accord with these principles. So, for instance, if I am faced with a decision that affects other I try to choose what is fairest and not what is best for me. Or if I need to resist temptation/make a decision as to what I want to do with my life going forward, I evaluate what will accord best with my values as above; a specific example of the latter would be when I'm struggling with eating healthily. There are many times I feel the temptation to eat poorly because of the short-term pleasure, but by evaluating what is important to me, I am able to resist the temptation.

ValuesSurvey: My central and most important values are guided by the saying "To thine own self be true."  I believe in living an authentic life.  I am always attempting to work through my conditioning and trauma to become the most authentic version of myself.  I believe in mindfulness.  I use mindfulness to help me get through difficult moments and to live in the present moment.  I was not taught how to deal with my emotions and that became a huge challenge when I became an adult.  I am highly interested in psychology and why people behave the way they do.  I've learned that this heightened sense of curiosity comes from the fact that I always felt hyper-aware of my mother's emotions.  She was not verbally affectionate and communicating with her was difficult as a child.  Not only was there a language barrier because she's from South Korea but she wasn't taught how to deal with her emotions either.  This naturally trickled down to me and I was always walking on eggshells around her mood swings as a child.  I had to manage her moods and this later became a strength and curse for me as an adult.  I'm a Myers Brigg's INFJ.  I have a very strong intuition and notice patterns in people automatically.  I had to learn how to use this as a gift rather than a curse.  It was hard to manage in my relationships once I got older but with conscious awareness and practice, I have been able to use mindfulness to use it to my advantage.

ValuesSurvey: I try to live by the oft repeated, but rarely actualized, motto of treat people how you want to be treated. I have seen many people in life treat others as if they are beneath them or owe them something, but when the time comes and they don't get the treatment they want they are upset. I think treating people how you would like to be treated is something that comes true because others see how you act. People can see how you behave and how you treat people, and if you are kind and generous they will likely be that same way towards you. I also know that if you are unkind or rude to someone, you should be ready to accept that same treatment back. How you treat people is a show of respect for other people and a show of respect for yourself as well. How you treat other people is how much respect you have for them and if you want this treatment back, how much respect you have for yourself.

ValuesSurvey: My most central values that guide my life are, my parents number one, and overall the teachings they have taught me over the years. For one, my father has always taught me to work hard and to work for myself, and that in life nothing is easy but it will take hard work and a lot of time. He has always taught me that there's always a solution for everything in life no matter the circumstances. If there are any problems in life, he has taught me that no matter how tough life is, that life will keep moving. When I have made some of the most difficult decisions I have always asked for his advice and has always been straightforward and pretty much everything that he has taught me in life has been straight forward. When I have dealt with difficult things in my life that is how I have continued life. I said "Its happened there is nothing else I can do, life goes on" An example of this, is for example, accidentally dropping my phone and it breaking it. It is replaceable. My father has always told me, "everything IS irreplaceable, except life". While we hold on to material things, every one of those material things will always be replaceable. But our very lives are not. These are the values that I have lived by. And the values are integrity, honesty, hard work, focus, patience, and straightforwardness. There is a solution for everything and in life. And there is always a better tomorrow.

BehaviorsSurvey:
So this whole mindfulness thing has really been popular as of late. There is a simple reason for that: it works. And from personal experience, it works well.

Perhaps you want to get started, but you tell yourself, or your busy mind tells you, that you just don’t have the time to sit around and meditate during the day. My first piece of advice is to take the time to observe your mind from an outside perspective and simply be in the moment. That is what meditation is all about. But this isn’t an article about meditation.

Despite what you think, meditating is not the only way to be mindful. My next piece of advice is to be mindful in your day-to-day activities. You can experience a meditative and mindful state merely by giving complete attention and awareness to the things you are doing in the present moment.

ValuesSurvey: I remember being a baby.  I knew no words.  All I could do was move my head and my eyes.  Every once in a while I would see "my" foot kick and I'd think (not in words but in impressions) what's up with that?  Oddly my inabilities were not a source of consternation to me then.  After all I no idea what to expect from.  Having a body with physical senses was brand new to me.  I had a certain patience about the whole situaton, like All would be revealed in the fullness of time.  I loved to hear my parents talk in the next room though I had no idea what they were saying.   But I knew how to pray. And it was easy(after all if it were difficult it would be essentially impossible for me).  If anyone had taught me about God I wouldn't have understood them (not in words anyway).  But KNEW there was a God.  And the concept of a name or names was alien to me.  And in an especially anxious moment I turned to God in prayer when I noticed my mother wasn't coming to see me.  And he answered that prayer a few days later.  I was praying for my mother who (unbeknowst to me then) was dying of viral pneumonia (and that's why she didn't come to see me).  And (also unbeknownst to me) her doctor had given her an experimental medicine that would either kill her or cure her.  And (also unbeknowst to me) she came home an decided to take it and it cured her.  I only later found out these things from my mother decades later.  And she said "And then I could come and see you again !".  Almighty God is close to me.  And he loves me, and you, too.
BehaviorsSurvey: I had spent 17 days in the hospital.  And 7 days ago I was sent home to recuperate from cardiac surgery (a new valve).  I have other health issues that I was so afraid would make it difficult for me to get out of the Uber ride.  But I became aware that the driver was a Christian.  So I asked her to pray for me as I got out of the vehicle, which she did.  Getting out was surprisingly easy.  And opening the lock with my brass key around my neck into a brass lock was also quite easy (perhaps a first for me because they tend to get gummy with corrosion).  I opened it up got her a tip and thanked her for praying for me as I believe so much could've gone wrong but did.  I'm rather poor and my insurance didn't cover rehab centers (I reckon) so they sent me home.  At first I was in bad shape (weak and sore) but happy to be home.  But my strength grew and the soreness faded.  Now my battle is with the bills.  (overcharging that should've been covered by Medicare A).  I been learning about the effects of a protein deficiency and about a potassium deficiency and well as how to prevent constipation (for a while there I wondered if I had an obstructed bowel, but by the grace of God I had a good movement yesterday (I think) after 3 weeks without one.  Sometimes I'm afraid that I might be overwhelmed by a sea of medical bills and lose my home only to die of exposure by the side of the road.  But all things do work together for good to them that love the Lord and are called for his purposes.  I don't know the future.  I have many abilities (by the grace of God) that might be useful.  For decades I've taken the security of this nation as a personal responsibility, not an organizational responsibility of mine.  I believe (perhaps out of vanity) that my abilities of strategic planning and new analysis and other things are so special, so refined that to subject them to a chain of command would diminish them.  Perhaps that's hubris.  Perhaps that's not God's calling for me.  But I know this much: no amount of cold hard math, no human skill alone, is sufficient to win victory neither in a modern conflict nor in ancient times.  Divine inspiration can fill in the gaps when the cold hard math falls short.  Perhaps the nature of conflict itself makes that inevitable, i.e. that victory belongs as much to the greatest prophets, the greatest seers and the greatest military.  Perhaps now as long ago conflict is as much about the journey of the human soul and the search for truth as anything else.  Have a merry Christmas.

ValuesSurvey: Some of the most important values to me include responsibility, wisdom, liberty, independence, self-reliance, resilience, and self-reflection. I really try to gain a little bit of wisdom every day, and pass it on when appropriate. I take pride in being self-reliant and resilient, and that I am able to do things and make decisions on my own. I am proud of what I have overcome and how strong those things have made me. I live and breathe independent thinking, and try to encourage it in others, as I dislike being simply reactionary. I try to arrive at my decisions and opinions after thorough self-reflection and research, and tend not to follow crowds in most cases unless our values happen to overlap. Ultimately, I believe in liberty and responsibility, two sides of the same coin. I must be responsible if I want liberty, and there is freedom to be found in being responsible.

ValuesSurvey: One of my core values is accepting people without judgement, as much as possible. I value having a nonjudgmental attitude. This value has been important in my work as a child and family therapist. Counseling doesn't work well if the therapist is judgmental toward the client. This is crucial when working with teens. Teens pick up on any type of judgement quickly and easily. I have also imparted this value to my kids and they have grown into adult who are nonjudgement as well as people who advocate for those struggling to be accepting in society. I also believe in compassion. We all have our stories and compassion allows us to connect as humans, though we may be different, politically or culturally, for example. I have been able to meet some amazing people by opening myself up and feeling compassion and empathy. I have been able to connect with strangers, if only through  brief conversations, in a deep way. This has added meaning to my life.

BehaviorsSurvey: I started a new embroidery project. I have this oddly-colored paisly print cotton fabric. I put a scrap of it in a small embroidery hoop and decided to experiment with embellishing the design printed on the fabric. I started with a black fuzzy floss. It says wool on it's label but I seriously doubt it is real wool. For the price I paid it is more likely to be acrylic than wool. Also, I've never seen wool sold before as stranded embroidery floss. But I started with one strand of the black and followed the outline with backstitches. When I ran out of that strand, I tried doing the same thing with a brown sewing thread. . The black floss was thicker than the printed line I was following and it looked bolder and darker with the thick floss. The brown thread was not quite as thick as the line I was following. Also, the brown was lighter than the black line printed on the fabric. The brown complimented the warm red on the print and the off-white of the background. I thought the brown thread looked muted but very nice on the print.

ValuesSurvey:
That one is easy for me.  You see, I had an afterlife experience, and even though I was resentful about having to come back for about twenty years, I came to accept the fact that I had to stay here for a reason.

Though the years, I have come across people who are either struggling with their faith, have lost or about to lose a loved one or facing death themselves.  I haven't really sought them out but when the opportunity arises, I love to share my story and assure them (straight from someone who isn't necessarily a 'bible thumper'), that we really do indeed go on to another level of existence after we leave our lives here, so they shouldn't be afraid.

I try to remind people on facebook, as I have hundreds of followers, to be kind, and morally kind and faithful to themselves and higher ideals.  So that is my mission now.

ValuesSurvey:
The most important values that guide my life is Focus and Appreciation Being able to concentrate on a particular activity and give it our full attention. When you can “zero in” on a specific outcome, you will be successful more often than not. Refocusing your attention is all about adjusting your mental lens. Just like you can change the lens on a camera to make your target object more precise, the same thing can be done with your mind. Having the ability to improve your mind, improve your brain, and quickly and effortlessly adjust your focus on one thing will bring about the positive results you want to achieve.
Using the Law of Attraction, the primary advantage of being in the mental and emotional space of gratitude and appreciation is that it helps you to live in a reality where everything works out in your favor. You set it free to explore itself. In the silence, you begin to get the insights and the inspirations and make the connections that take you out of mind into consciousness, which is beyond reason. Being inspired, feeling gratitude, and appreciating life cannot be experienced if you are stuck in your mind.

ValuesSurvey:
The most important thing to me is helping others.  The main way I do that is through my work.  I work as part of a commissions team, and part of my role is to make sure that the payments we make are accurate.  I spend many hours each day reviewing the data from many standpoints to ensure our payments will be as accurate as possible.  I make sure that the right amount is paid on the right deals in the right month to the right people.  It is a matter of pride to me and to my team, and a matter of trust between us and the people we pay.  I monitor our systems proactively to prevent issues from happening.

Another way that I help people is through one-on-one training.  Since our team works remotely, I tend to interact with my co-workers through video calls and screen shares.  Sometimes I share my screen, but more often I let them share their screen.  This way I can watch as they walk me through the process they are asking me about.  I can see what parts they understand and where they could use some help, then I teach them how to work through their issue - whether it's how to create a report or view to monitor their activity, or where to look to find the information they are missing.  By educating and empowering my co-workers, I am helping them to become more productive, and helping them to succeed, which gives me a sense of pride and purpose.

Last Saturday, my youngest son and I went Christmas shopping together.  I drove, and we went to a large mall about 40 minutes away.  We stopped at several stores while looking for a particular store which had apparently gone out of business, since we never did find it.  We got hungry so we went to the food court and picked up some food at Taco Bell.  The food court is right under the movie theaters, which put us in the mood to see a movie.  We headed upstairs and found out that the movie we wanted to see would start in about an hour. 
 That gave us time to take our purchases out to the car, then come back and get our tickets plus some munchies.  After the movie we stopped at one more store then headed home.   On Sunday, my oldest son and I went Christmas shopping. He drove, and we went to his favorite hobby shop, about an hour away.  Next we got lunch at Taco Bell (a family favorite), then went to a book store, then came home.   We sat by the wood stove and watched Netflix until supper, then he headed back to his house.  Monday through Friday I worked from my home office during the day and watched Netflix in the evenings.  On Wednesday, my oldest son's girlfriend stopped by to visit and we sat by the wood stove and talked between work and Netflix.

ValuesSurvey: Having love for someone is a very important value to me. I love my family, friends, and my pets. Showing that love is important as well, so that the ones I truly care about can see that I love and care for them as well. Respect is another important value to me. If someone doesn't show me respect when I am giving it to them, it shows that I don't need this person in my life. It means that they don't care about me, so I shouldn't waste my time on them.

I have baked a cake for my culinary school assignment. I have cooked a few meals for lunch and dinner. I have visited my moms house to see her. I have wrapped Christmas presents and put them under my tree. I have feed and played with my pets everyday. I have worked on my phone every day. I have played video games and watched YouTube videos everyday. I have taken a shower and brushed my teeth everyday. I have talked to my friends and family everyday.

ValuesSurvey: Important values that guide my life, are god first in everything. Without him we would not even be here on this earth. Doing good deeds and treating others with respect. It's not good to get even with people when they do you wrong. You always have to think about the good in everything. Being respectful to your elderly people and always saying thank you and please. Going out of your way once and a while helping out a stranger that you don't know. You never know what something as simple as paying for someones meal, or opening a door, or giving them a compliment can do to someone. It could make their entire day. Having your heart in the good is always a plus.
BehaviorsSurvey: Over the passed 7 days I have been christmas shopping online and in store, wrapping presents that I have already gotten. It was ok though, it's all about the memories being made. I have also went grocery shopping which we do every week.

ValuesSurvey: I've come up with my own honor code depending on what I feel at the time. I pretty much live my life the way I feel and educated guesses on civilization. I'm quick to analyze everything told to me, so I don't make any mistakes. I like to be able to adapt like water as Bruce Lee said.

ValuesSurvey: One of my guiding values is simplicity. This simplicity extends from modest consumption to fewer but closer relationships. Simplicity as a guiding value can provide a lower stress, less competitive existence. This may sound simple in itself, but arguably difficult in the context of a consumer driven society, where more is better. Simplicity can be a good approach to lower consumption driven climate change; unfortunately, society promotes consumption and comparison.
BehaviorsSurvey: Most of the past week is a routine of managing a child in my home. This includes meals, transportation to and from school, and leisure activities. Of course, each day starts with morning activities to get ready for the day, and after having something to eat, heading out into the world. Most weekday routines are similar, returning to prepare dinner, eat, dishes, followed by evening routines of television, bathing, brushing, etc. Weekends often include laundry, errands such as grocery, and other leisure activities.

ValuesSurvey: My main value in life is to experience as much as I possibly can. I believe each person is put on this earth to see and do and explore as much as they possibly can. I constantly try to integrate new experiences in my life and constantly switch up my routine. I believe sitting stagnantly is the number one way to waste your life. I am always trying to make new friends and go new places. I believe somewhere along the way as you are growing, changing, and evolving you find your true purpose in life. Without new experiences and meeting new people we never truly grow. New places and people inspire and teach us things that we could never learn otherwise.
BehaviorsSurvey: Last weekend I started Christmas shopping. I went to several different stores and made several orders online. On Monday I went to work and did my regular shift duties such as stocking shelves and assisting customers. That night I got chic-fil-a for dinner for me and my boyfriend. On Tuesday I adopted a new kitten named Yona. On Wednesday I went to Walmart to get all the necessary supplies for my new kitten. Then I came home and set up her litterbox and played with her for a few hours. On Thursday I went out bowling with some friends. We ended up going out for drinks afterwards. Today I laid in bed and watched some of my favorite horror movies while cuddling with my new kitten and my dog Lucy. Then I decided to get on Mturk and work for a few hours.

ValuesSurvey: my biggest value is Honesty and speaking the truth and never trying not to lie. I hate when people say different things depending who they are with. for me it is important to say the truth and never say a lie. another value that I have is my family. they mean everything to me. they are the one who I can turn to for all my problems. they have helped me through out my life. I am who I am because of them. My other value is loyalty. I can never think about betraying someone who put their trust in me. I always try to think how I will feel if who I trust is not trustworthy.
BehaviorsSurvey: My week is very basic and same. I will  write about Monday and all the other days are pretty much the same except Saturday and Sunday. We start Monday with my husband going to work. I prepare his shake and lunch and send him off to work. Then I go to sleep and wake up a little later with my two kids. Rest of the day goes behind my two kids. I gave them breakfast and then I gave them a bath. we eat and do Our routine for the day. They play and I work on Mturk. We eat dinner together with my husband at the end of the day. We try to go out on weekends and do something different from the weekdays

ValuesSurvey: This one doesn't sound as easy as the seven days but I'll give it a try. My guiding principals consist of whatever I feel is best for my family. My family is what guides my decisions, along with what is right from wrong. I try to instill values that teach my children to not judge others based on race, religion, sexuality, size and so on, and I do my best to lead by example.
BehaviorsSurvey: Let's see, what have I done in the past seven days? Well last Friday I spent the day at home cleaning and doing laundry then in the late afternoon I took two of my teenage sons and mother-in-law Christmas shopping. It was a fun evening and we weren't out to late. Saturday was a day at home, decorating the house and Christmas tree. Sunday, again, a day at home. We finished the lights on the house, final decorations on the tree and my husband left for Illinois. Monday was a day of schoolwork, teaching a history class for our local home school cooperative. After teaching, my two sons and myself met my oldest son for dinner at a local Mexican restaurant, then off to Walmart for them to find White Elephant gifts for a Drama class party the next day. Next day is here, Tuesday. Woke up early to bake cookies and wrap gifts for their teachers and for their white elephant gift exchange. Drama is a little over an hour drive so we, two boys, mother-in-law and myself,  left early, stopped for fuel and a quick lunch before dropping them off for three hours of fun. Spent the next two and half hours helping my mother-in-law get all of her Christmas shopping complete. After our final store we headed back to pick the boys up from their party and our hour drive home. The hour drive turned in to more like one and three quarters an hour due to an accident on the freeway. After getting home, changing clothes, wrapping one last gift and gathering the supplies we were back out the door for their Teen Night Christmas party, local home school group, I had organized at a community center in a town near us. Two and half hours of fun, visiting and another gift exchange then it was home, sandwiches for dinner and pajamas. Finally ten o'clock, devices off, everyone to your rooms and asleep by eleven. Yay! Tuesday is over and Wednesday was just grocery shopping and dinner at home.

ValuesSurvey: My family means more to me than anything.  I would do almost anything for them.  I will go without things in order to provide things for my sons.  I have a hard time spending money on things that I want when I know that there are things that my sons need.  I make sure that they make good grades and that they have food to eat at home.  I like being a care giver.  I like teaching and guiding.  I love to see my sons learn new things.
BehaviorsSurvey: I started getting ready for Christmas.  My house needed to be decorated and the gifts needed to be wrapped.  On the first day, I got my Christmas tree out of storage.  I put it up and decorated it.  This took me several hours to complete the task.  The next day I gathered up all of the Christmas gifts that I had bought over the past few days.  I separated them into piles according to who they were going to.  I spent about an hour each night for 3 nights wrapping these gifts and putting them under the trees.  And last but not least, I planned out my Christmas day dinner menu.

ValuesSurvey: My family is the most important thing in my life. My husband and I have a grown Autistic son. It is my goal to make sure he is happy and well cared for. We own a 300 acre farm. The farm animals and our cats and dogs are good therapy. We raise a huge garden that we all work in. It makes us appreciate good food. Vegtables taste so much better right out of the garden.Just loving each other and making sure we all are happy and well cared for is the most important thing in the world to me. We live a simple life, but it is so fulfilling.
BehaviorsSurvey: My family get up every day at 6 a.m. We begin our day with a nice breakfast, and coffee. After we eat we go out and feed our 100 head of cattle. We check them over and count them. If a cow is hollering there is usually something wrong. After that we go home for a break, then we do the household chores. After lunch we go back out and work. In the winter we work on equipment, clean up barns. Straighten up the work room. Around 4 we go back in get a bath, and fix supper. On top of all of this we have been getting ready for Christmas. we got our tree up, Made some fudge, and some other good candy that we will hand out to our neighbors on Christmas Eve.

ValuesSurvey: My first guiding value/behavior is kindness.  I treat people with kindness and respect.  Everyone deserves my best efforts, it's not only the right thing to do for others but for me as well.  I also value the generosity of spirit. I feel we are here to help one another, it's a primary purpose for humans.  We need to care for each other, all people we meet.  I believe we are spirits, we have a human body but we're spirits and I don't find it difficult to "lead" with my spirit.  I enjoy interacting with others very much.  I learn a lot about myself as much as of the other person.  Over-riding all my behaviors is being genuine.  Being authentic is the most important thing in all I do.
BehaviorsSurvey: Over the last week, I had a bit of a cold, I spent some of last weekend sleeping and napping.  I tried to stay away from others as I didn't want to pass along my cold.  The first few weekdays I worked from home, on a reduced schedule as I was up to date on my work.  There were emails and texts to deal with but it was a light load.  On Wednesday I was in need of some grocery store supplies so I went to replenish some items.  I was feeling much better so I  made plans to go out to breakfast with my sister to a spot we both enjoy and a friend is a waitress.  Then we did a bit of Christmas shopping.  We had some laughs and lots of fun.  Today was also a work-from-home day.  It was a half-day as well.

ValuesSurvey:
The most important values in my life are integrity, kindness, and gratitude. 
Having integrity is staying true to yourself and doing the right thing when no one is watching. I think it’s important for people to always act right. Kindness is treating others the way you want to be treated. If everyone did that the world would be a better place. Gratitude is being thankful for life and the things you have. I think it’s important to find positivity during tough times.

ValuesSurvey: The most important values in my life are related to my faith.  1 have a few things that I try to live by.  To Whom much is given much is required.  I believe that I have been blessed and I feel that I should use talent and give when I have the opportunity.  I believe that you should work hard in life because you work to honor God, people are watching and you represent your upbringing.  How you act and what you say is representative of your family, the company you work for or your household.  Another value that I live by is to be a good steward.  Don't spend tomorrow's prosperity.   I learned this early on by going through bad circumstances and fortunately, one time.  I made a point of learning about preparation, saving and investing, as well as trying to advantage of opportunities that come along or learning different things.

ValuesSurvey: I am here to serve and, on occasion, when I have the opportunity, to pursue my own interests.  The most important thing for me is for me to do what I can to support my wife and children.  There is something to be said for God, Country, and Family, in that order, and that's always in the back of my head.  I wish it was actually more in the for front of my thoughts instead!  I guess I try to treat others like I like to be treated, but I have no expectation on others about that.  It makes me happy when I can help others be happy, but, more often than not, I am engrossed in my work of the day.  Regardless, I still try to live up to those ideals.  Here's another basic guiding principle for me:  Ideally, I am 1/3 student, 1/3 teach, and 1/3 doer - and sometimes these fractions differ depending on the situation, but I strive for balance.

ValuesSurvey: A central value that guides my life is being kind to people. I always think that you never know what a person is going to, so I like to make sure that I am polite and don't treat people rudely. I also believe in equality, and I think it is important that people are treated fairly.  Another central value of my life is perseverance. I have been through a lot of different things, so I always try to keep my life on track and keep going.
BehaviorsSurvey: In the past seven days, I went to work, I fulfilled Instacart orders, and I hung out with my friends. Monday, I called off of work because I was not feeling well. I don't really remember anything else that I did specifically for the rest of the week. Aside from my obligations, I was with my friends and we partook in various activities such as watching shows, ordering food, and playing video games.

ValuesSurvey: AFter losing my husband to an abrupt and sudden death, everything about life looks different, I've come to realize that all the things I used to consider important, like career, success, money, traveling are all secondary to family, friends, love, time spent together. Those things aren't bad, but I realize that spending a day with my grandaughter, talking about her tween drama over lunch, laying on the couch talking about life in general, is so much more fulfilling than spending a day at work creating the next best marketing strategy. Talking on the phone with my grandson about his wife being pregnant and how his life just went from being a college kid waiting tables to graduating from college, taking a job at a school this semester and a baby on the way. He just hit serious adulthood, discussing it at length with him is so much more fulfilling than creating e-mail campaigns for the company I work for. If I could go back in time, my career would ALWAYS come second my family would ALWAYS come first. My friends, my family, the relationships, in the end, they are all that matters. My volunteer work is a critical part of my identity as well, but again, if I had to rearrange things in my life in order of importance, Family, FRiends, Volunteer work, career.
BehaviorsSurvey: Two friends and I went to a movie in Springfield, about 30 minutes from our hometown. After the movie, we went to eat at Applebee's and then drove home later that night. The following morning I went to Church, after Church I came home and started decorating my house with Christmas decorations. Before coming home after church though I stopped at a deli and picked up enough food that I didn't have to cook for myself all day or run back into town to get something to eat. The next day which was Monday, I went to work but left early because I felt kind of sick. On my way home, I stopped by Wal-Mart to buy some Christmas tree lights and some storage bins so I could organize things in my extra bedroom which has become a catch-all and looks kind of like something you'd see on hoarders. By the time I got home, (which is 45 minutes from where I work) I was feeling full-fledged sick and went straight to bed without eating anything, By Tuesday morning I knew I had something pretty nasty so I called in sick to work and spent the rest of the day on the couch sneezing and coughing. Nothing tasted good, I kept trying to find anything satisfying but absolutely nothing...except for Noosa Vanilla Bean Yogurt tasted good. Wednesday my son brought some food over so I didn't have to go to the store and I spent Wednesday and Thursday in bed. I missed the Christmas party at CHurch Thursday night with all the girls from our ladies' Bible Study. Friday my grandson was graduating from the University of Missouri so I forced myself to get ready and go to the graduation. After graduation, the whole family went to Longhorn Steakhouse and I had a Prime Rib that was amazing. I drove home in a downpour and nearly ran off the road twice because of poor visibility. I made it home safely and went back to bed.
